<HEAD>Aeroperu Plane Crashes, 12 People Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with new death toll now at 12; American and
Europeans reported among dead; US Embassy comment; EDITS to TRIM. No
Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Aeroperu plane carrying 69 people crashed seconds after takeoff Tuesday from an Andes airport and airline officials said 12 people were killed, including an American and three Europeans. Aeroperu spokesman <PERSON> Freddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirinos </PERSON> said 56 people were injured and one person could not be accounted for. Survivors said there was an explosion aboard the Dutch-built <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> F-28 just after it departed from the <LOCATION> Manco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Capac </LOCATION> airport at <LOCATION> Juliaca </LOCATION>, 540 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. In a brief communique the state-operated airline said an American was among the dead and identified him as <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, but listed no hometown. It said other foreigners killed were <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ervert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ingeborg </PERSON> <PERSON> Psiller </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, but did not provide hometowns. Transportation Minister <PERSON> Camilo </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrillo </PERSON> told reporters in <LOCATION> Juliaca </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellina </PERSON>, the pilot of Flight 771, swerved the stricken craft in an effort to return to the runway but it crashed in a pasture. Witnesses said the twin-jet plane broke in two and the rear section burst into flames, and many of the injured suffered burns. Officials said an investigation was underway to determine the cause of the accident. In its list of people who perished, the communique said the bodies of three victims had not been identified and five Peruvians were killed, including an airline hostess. <PERSON> Chirinos </PERSON> said the four dead foreigners were among at least 19 non-Peruvians aboard. He did not have the hometowns of any of the foreigners. He said <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunning </PERSON> and <PERSON> Katherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Kraus </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Luana </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gianinazzi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> were hospitalized in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> with grave injuries. The identified the 11 foreigners treated at the <LOCATION> Juliaca </LOCATION> hospital as <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Savoir </PERSON>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Krankin </PERSON>, all with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> passports; <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Koyson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brigitte </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kabin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Joacy </PERSON> <PERSON> Borge </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ana </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gina </PERSON> <PERSON> Garfias </PERSON> all of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Officials at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said they had no information about the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> victims. The plane was en route from <LOCATION> Juliaca </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Arequipa </LOCATION>, 120 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Juliaca </LOCATION>. Tourists often take the flight to return from visits to <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Titicaca </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Juliaca </LOCATION> Airline and Puno state officials earlier had given different casualty figures, saying as many as 22 people had been killed. Aeroperu president <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerra </PERSON> had said 19 people died. <PERSON> Aeroperu </PERSON> said the plane had a capacity load of 65 passengers and four crew members. Police in <LOCATION> Juliaca </LOCATION> said four Peruvian legislators _ a sentator and three congressmen _ were among the victims. One of the lawmakers, Congressman <PERSON> Rolando </PERSON> <PERSON> Avila </PERSON> told reporters in <LOCATION> Juliaca </LOCATION> that the aircraft had traveled only about 400 yards after takeoff when the lights went out and there was an explosion. `` I thought our hour had arrived,'' <PERSON> Avila </PERSON> said. `` Everyone panicked. The pilots apparently tried to level off to land and the plane scraped the roofs of some adobe homes before falling near a small river.'' <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerra </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Aeroperu </ORGANIZATION> president, said the plane crashed one minute after taking off at 10:45 a.m. The airline said that within seconds after takeoff the pilot radioed the Juliaca tower saying the plane was losing altitude, he was returning and asked for emergency crews to stand by. Two months ago the <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeroperu </ORGANIZATION> issued a statment claiming the airline's planes were in bad shape because of shortages of spare parts. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> is virtually out of foreign currency reserves because of its economic crisis and is unable to import equipment for many of its industries. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s last major air accident occurred Dec. 9 when a twin-engine <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> F-27 crashed off the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> coast, killing 44 people including most of the members of the <LOCATION> Lianza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> soccer team.
