<HEAD>Attorney Says Engineer Recruited By Egyptian Defense Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An attorney for a rocket expert accused in a $ 1 million scheme to smuggle American missile technology to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> said Tuesday that <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> officials claimed the operation had been approved by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government. <PERSON> Marcus </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Topel </PERSON>, an attorney for <PERSON> Abdelkader </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmy </PERSON>, an Egyptian-born <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen who was a rocket specialist at the <ORGANIZATION> Aerojet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Propulsion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, said the American government possesses a report from <LOCATION> Egyptian </LOCATION> officials making that claim. <PERSON> Topel </PERSON> said he is attempting to obtain the document as part of his defense for <PERSON> Helmy </PERSON>, 40, who is jailed on a no-bail warrant pending a trial expected to begin next spring. <PERSON> Topel </PERSON> said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> government documents also support his contention that his client was recruited by <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s defense minister, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Abdel-Halim </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu-Ghazala </PERSON>. In papers filed Monday in federal <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Topel </PERSON> said <PERSON> Helmy </PERSON> met twice with <LOCATION> Abu-Ghazala </LOCATION> _ in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> in September 1987 and in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last March. The papers said the general asked for <PERSON> Helmy </PERSON>'s aid in buying material for an Egyptian military research and development program. <PERSON> Topel </PERSON> identified the program as a joint effort with <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and perhaps other countries to develop medium-range missiles. `` Our investigation has shown these meetings did occur,'' <PERSON> Topel </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` We expect at an appropriate time in trial to provide more than sufficient evidence that the meetings occurred. ... The appropriate time is not now.'' <PERSON> Helmy </PERSON>, his wife and another <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> were charged last June with money laundering and conspiring illegally to export technology for sophisticated weapon systems. Two colonels in the Egyptian army also were accused in the case but claimed diplomatic immunity. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities claim <PERSON> Helmy </PERSON> received $ 1 million in payments from Egyptians for his role involving the illicit export of a substance called carbon-carbon or carbon composite. The material is a low-radar-visibility compound used in missile nose cones and Stealth aircraft. They accuse <PERSON> Helmy </PERSON> of belonging to an international export ring illegally sending sensitive material to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> has said it is cooperating with the investigation, but President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> has said the Egyptian defendants were guilty only of procedural errors and had committed no crimes. Federal prosecutors have declined comment on the defense allegations. They have until Nov. 7 to file a formal response in District Court. A hearing is scheduled for Dec. 1.
