<HEAD>U.S.-Canada Free Trade Pact Dominates Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Editing and new material throughout, UPDATING with debate
finale. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The U.S.-Canada free trade agreement negotiated by Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> dominated the debate Tuesday among leaders of the three major parties in a critical prelude to the Nov. 21 election. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said the agreement achieved by his <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was central to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s future and he described his rivals' attacks against the pact as `` scare mongering.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON> of the socialist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> criticized <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> and then argued about who had most effectively opposed the agreement. The three-hour, English-language debate was broadcast nationally from <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> and followed a three-hour French-language debate Monday night. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said the agreement, scheduled to take effect Jan. 1, will allow <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to move ahead and compete internationally to assure future prosperity. He challenged his foes to outline an effective alternative. `` They would tear up the free trade agreement and then what? They offer you nothing but the poverty of protectionism,'' he said. Turner again vowed to battle the pact. `` This election is not a popularity contest. The issue is the future of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` He -LRB- <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> -RRB- now wants to turn us into a pale replica of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' Polls early in the campaign that began Oct. 1 generally placed the Conservatives first, with at least 40 percent of the vote usually needed for a majority government. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> called the election Oct. 1 after serving four years of his maximum five-year term. He won a landslide victory in 1984 and is seeking to put together a second consecutive majority government, which has not happened in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> since 1953. The New Democrats pushed the Liberals to third in most polls before the debates. That would be a stunning setback for the party of former Prime Minister <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Trudeau </PERSON>. <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON> also strongly attacked the free trade agreement. `` This deal must be stopped because it takes away our right to make decisions about our own country in our own way,'' he said. Critics of the trade pact say the huge population and economic power of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would force <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to renounce social welfare programs and regional development plans. `` What we have here is a deal that touches virtually every aspect of Canadian life,'' <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said, `` I hope Canadians defeat this deal by defeating Mr. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> responded by saying Canadians are fully capable of competing internationally and there was `` not the slightest justification'' for raising fears of loss of identity or social protections. `` You've been scare mongering,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted, 83-9, in September in favor of the trade agreement signed in January by <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, however, only the elected House of Commons controlled by the Conservatives passed it. Liberals in the non-elected <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> balked and kept the agreement bottled up. A <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> win with a parliamentary majority would let the world's two largest trading partners proceed to form a North American free trade zone on Jan. 1, eliminating all tariffs over a 10-year period and dismantling barriers to investment and competition. A Gallup poll published Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> found support for the agreement slippng, with 42 percent of Canadians opposed and 34 percent in favor. The others said they had no opinion or neither supported nor opposed the proposal.
