<HEAD>Ungaro Summer Offerings Mostly A Variation Of Last Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Summer sirens in sizzling colors and clinging short skirts ambled down the runway at <ORGANIZATION> Emanuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ungaro </ORGANIZATION>'s summer ready-to-wear show. While the rest of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> is easing up on summer profiles with many dropped hemlines, <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON> went his own way _ fitting, draping and adding little bows to sexy outfits. Most of the dozens of looks in Tuesday's long and somewhat monotonous show were variations on last year's. There were countless gorgeous but familiar nipped-waist spencer jackets with long points, plus plenty of peplums above the body-hugging skirts. The newer flowing babydoll jackets in hot colors are easier toppers. Varied fabrics were mixed in an outfit, another Ungaro forte. His new short skirt is shiny red, burgundy or brown patent leather, teamed up with flowered blouses and jackets. <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON>'s flower garden sprouted all kinds of posies, in every spring color imaginable from pink to robin's egg blue to lime, fuchsia and amethyst. The decorator's dream prints were heavily charged with big peonies and roses, but the best flower jackets were simpler _ white pique sprigged with wild flowers. <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON>'s pants are original. Instead of the favorite wide pantskirt, he chose droopy drawers, long or short fluid harem or bloomer pants, teamed up with the showy, flowered fitted tops. Evening wear with plenty of lace and lame was predictably flounced and elaborate looking, as most of the show did, a dead-ringer for couture. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Douvier </PERSON>'s styles for <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Laroche </PERSON> were much simpler and undoubtedly will be less expensive. This clean-cut collection featured short skirts, smart pea jackets and long, straight pants or shorts in red, white and navy nautical lines. Careful cut and finish gave blue or gray denim skirts and shorts suits smooth city elegance. Big color prints burst out here, too, on flowered strapless bustier sheaths with puff-sleeved boleros. Other feminine lines in turquoise, fuchsia and yellow were paneled and wrapped like flower petals. And with all this color, <PERSON> Douvier </PERSON> was dotty over black polka dots on the hot colors. <PERSON> Jean-Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Scherrer </PERSON> showed a huge group of navy-and-white nautical outfits, beautifully cut with flowing trousers, and neat variations on the pea jacket, as well as lots of stripes. <PERSON> Scherrer </PERSON> showed full shorts and a striped mini-jersey, but he usually preferred less leggy looks. A white pique sundress with a long, swirling skirt and little blue jacket could be a winner. There were enough safari outfits and jungle prints here to make a planter pleased as punch. In desert shades of sand and burnt orange, or printed in green and violet, they ranged from sexy tulip-draped skirts to belted but full light cotton bush jackets over ample long pants. For after-hours, <PERSON> Scherrer </PERSON> opted for flowered, draped sheaths or lacy inspiration in short or long evening dresses of expensive lingerie inspiration. The froths of lace bubbled all over like champagne, including the soft peach and sky blue dressy evening pyjamas, and bustier dresses with silk chiffon blazers. <PERSON> Scherrer </PERSON> ended the show with navy lame and lurex sailor suits, quite handsome indeed for the skipper or first mate on the night watch. <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON> also was big on lace. But he did n't seem to know where to stop, pairing it with chiffon prints and huge swaths of rhinestone embroidery. On some outfits it looked demure; on others, it was rather heavy-handed. Day wear was more successful, especially the suits _ lean, short and sleek as only <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON> knows how to make them. He showed very pure lines in battle-jacket tops, or easily fitted glen plaid or checked jackets over white pique vests, silk blouses underneath. <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON>'s favorite trouser line still looked new, straight and not too full, with a cuff at the ankle. Other trousers included short, full culottes, lean pedal pushers _ topped by boxy plaid jackets. <PERSON> Erik </PERSON> <PERSON> Mortensen </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Balmain </LOCATION> was applauded for a collection that looked both simple and elegant. His idea of the trapeze pants was a suit in awning stripes of red or green, topped with a neat little bolero. Suits were lean, dressy and short, sometimes cut in diagonal, two-colored combinations. And <PERSON> Mortensen </PERSON>'s clinging ribbed knit dresses in hot shades of red, orange and yellow were intriguingly textured with panels of the ribbed knit cut so the ribbing was placed at several angles all over the dress.
