<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yields Mixed on Short-Term T-Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities were mixed in the latest auction. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 7.0 billion in three-month bills Monday at an average discount rate of 7.45 percent, up from 7.36 percent last week. Another $ 7.0 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.54 percent, down from 7.55 percent last week. The three-month rate was the highest since the bills sold for 7.69 percent on May 13, 1985. The six-month rate was the lowest since the bills averaged 7.46 on Oct. 11. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 7.70 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,811.70 and 7.95 percent for six-month bills selling for $ 9,618.80. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 8.12 percent last week after averaging 8.07 percent the week before.
