<FIRST>r w PM-Treasury-Dollar     10-25 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury-Dollar,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Planning Currency Talks With Taiwan, South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is preparing for a new round of talks with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> about what it considers unfair efforts to bolster their trade balances by manipulating the value of their currencies. The omnibus trade bill passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this summer required the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to determine if four newly industrialized <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries _ <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> _ are artificially holding down value of their currencies relative to the dollar. The report, delivered to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> banking committees on Monday, found that <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, while running large trade surpluses, impose few restrictions on trade. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, however, keep their currencies artificially low and impose tariffs and other barriers to free trade, the report said. The failure of the <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> dollar and Korean won to appreciate significantly against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar keeps prices of American exports to those countries high and the price of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports of Taiwanese and South Korean products low. A senior <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, noted that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has discussed the exchange rate issue with <LOCATION> Tawian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> before, but said the trade bill represented `` a very significant change in terms of perception.'' Although it does not specify penalties against countries manipulating their currencies, the bill requires the administration to assess the result of the negotiations in six months. `` If there's a lack of progress, we will have to report that,'' the official said. The new talks will begin `` as soon as we can effectively commence the dialogue,'' he said. In general, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it was pleased by the progress of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its economic allies in stabilizing exchange rates since the Louvre Accord in February 1987. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and economists have expressed alarm at the 14 percent rise, at an annual rate, in the value of the dollar from lows nine months ago, saying it will hamper progress on whittling down the trade deficit. However, the report said the dollar, by rising this year, had simply rebounded from a drop it characterized as a temporary overreaction to the October stock market crash and that the dollar was still lower than before the crash. `` It seems unlikely that movements in the dollar so far this year will significantly alter the outlook for sustained trade ... improvement,'' it said. The report strongly endorsed efforts by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which had the largest trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, to stimulate its economy in an effort to increase import buying. It said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which had the second largest trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, has also moved in the right direction, but said, `` its performance is less striking.'' Overall, the official predicted the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> current account, which includes trade in merchandise and the flow of investment dollars across borders, will shrink by $ 20 billion this year, from a peak in 1987 of $ 154 billion. The official said the improvement should continue next year, but declined to say by how much. Many private economists maintain the deficit will not shrink further without an additional drop in the dollar. Economists worry that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' status as the world's biggest debtor nation _ it owed $ 368 billion at the end of last year _ makes it vulnerable to a sharp drops in the value of the dollar or skyrocketing interest rates should foreigners decided to pull their money out But the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> said `` such concerns are exaggerated or unwarranted.'' It said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> debt in comparison to the size of its economy is modest by international standards and said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` remains an extremely attractive place to invest.'' In another part of the report, the administration said its policy of coordinating intervention in currency markets with other major industrial nations has proved `` more helpful than previously thought'' in stabilizing exchange rates even though the interventions were small relative to total currency trading. It said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> spent $ 8.5 billion to prop up the value of the dollar as it was falling in 1987 and sold $ 1.4 billion in dollars to curb its appreciation this year.
</TEXT>
