<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two jewels in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s musical crown, the <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> Symphony and coloratura soprano <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON>, presented a brilliant concert for this year's United Nations Day celebration on Monday night. The concert in the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> is an annual event commemorating the birth of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> on Oct. 24, 1945, and Secretary General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> greeted the audience with a brief statement before the performance. The appearance by the <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> Symphony, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s oldest musical institution, came as it makes its first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tour, which began Oct. 16 and continues through Nov. 6, part of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s Bicentennial celebrations PBS has televised U.N. Day concerts for 20 years. This year the concert will air on Wednesday at 9:30 p.m. EDT. After three instrumental pieces, conducted by <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Challender </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> sang some music from the first act of `` La Traviata,'' concluding with `` Sempre libera.'' Her husband, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonynge </PERSON>, conducted for her. A month before her 63rd birthday, her voice was glorious. Singing in the opera's original key, she hit every coloratura note squarely and with apparent ease, hit high notes without scooping up to them. After intermission, she sang the title character's entrance in `` The Merry Widow'' and `` Vilia,'' beautifully sustaining the mood of that haunting song. The concert ended with her singing from `` <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sonnambula </LOCATION>,'' one of the bel canto operas which introduced her to American audiences. She spun the melodic lines, made perfect delicate trills and was altogether thrilling. The concert began with `` Till Eulenspiegel's Merry Pranks'' by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>. <PERSON> Challender </PERSON> emphasized the lyricism of the music. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, with its wood strips on the walls and wooden desks, is acoustically warm, abetting the conductor's approach of making the music sing. Till's rudest pranks were not depicted in vulgar tones in this presentation. Next came `` The Display Suite,'' which Australian composer <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> took from his 1963 score for the Australian Ballet about a bird's wooing its mate. The suite is accessible and pleasing, beginning with an atonal introduction and the bird represented by a piccolo. A remarkably cheery waltz, sounding almost Viennese, follows. After that comes rich music for an unhurried love duet and a mildly percussive finale. The orchestra also played <PERSON> Ravel </PERSON>'s `` La Valse'' with <PERSON> Challender </PERSON> emphasizing the shimmer, while keeping tension and flow, and again downplaying any ominous undercurrents. The orchestra sounded fine. Not overwhelmed by the strings, the brass especially, and also woodwinds and percussion, made the most of their moments to shine.
