<SECOND>PM-Vincennes Homecoming,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Captain Denies Crew Stress Led to Downing of Iranian Airliner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The USS Vincennes came home to an emotional welcome after a six-month deployment marred by the crew's accidental downing of an Iranian jetliner over the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, killing the 290 people aboard `` We're glad to be home, I assure you of that,'' Capt. <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said after the guided-missile cruiser docked at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> on Monday. `` This is a nice place.'' <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>' 400-man crew cheered loudly as he walked down the gangway. The captain got a kiss, a hug and flowers from his wife, <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON>. After a brief welcoming ceremony, the sailors poured off the ship into a sea of relatives, friends and fellow servicemen. `` Hi, daddy. You're home!'' a little girl said as she waved to her father. Petty Officer 3rd Class <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hile </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Niles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, got a warm embrace from his girlfriend, <PERSON> Vallita </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawwill </PERSON>. `` I do n't even know what we were doing there,'' <PERSON> Hile </PERSON> said. `` It's a tragedy that it happened. But I'm glad I'm home and I'm alive. The <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> mistook the <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> jetliner for an Iranian F-14 fighter jet when it shot the aircraft down July 3, according to the official <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> report on the tragedy. The report concluded that the warship's crew misinterpreted computer and radar data because of the stress of being in combat for the first time. At the time, the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> was in a firefight with several Iranian gunboats. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> disputed that conclusion Monday. `` It's my opinon that stress was not a factor,'' he said. `` Given all of the information available and in view of the ongoing continuum of violent and aggressive Iranian action, I was convinced beyond any doubt that the inbound aircraft was in direct support of the surface engagement in progress,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said. `` There, of course, were mistakes made and there always are in an intense combat environment,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said. `` But both my crew and the system performed basically as designed. `` I, as well as my crew, will live with the result of the tragic loss of civilian lives associated with these actions, tempered only by the belief I had no other course of action and that any prudent commanding officer would do the same.'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said the fate of the USS Stark, on which 37 sailors died in an Iraqi missile attack in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, was in the back of his mind throughout his ship's mission. `` No skipper sails in the gulf without the Stark at least in your subconscious,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said. `` Was it a factor during that decision process? I do n't consciously remember.'' Responding to a question from an Iranian reporter, <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said he regretted the loss of civilian life. The captain said he knew within 90 minutes of ordering two missiles fired that the downed airplane was a civilian airliner. He said he later assembled the crew to tell them the news, which they took quietly. `` At first we were all devastated,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said. `` It goes without saying. But I have to look at it, and my crew looks at it, that given the fact that the airliner made no indication that it was not a hostile craft, we had no other choice.''
