<FIRST>r a PM-CarvingDispute     10-25 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carving Dispute,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thai Group Skeptical Over Museum Decision To Return Relic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to return a 1,000-year-old stone carving that <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> says disappeared from a sacred temple two decades ago, in hopes of ending a nine-month international dispute. But a Thai group says it wo n't be satisfied until its government approves the plan. `` We can not say that it is resolved until complete agreement is reached between the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and the Thai government,'' said <PERSON> Wutisak </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapcharoensap </PERSON>, spokesman of the Thai <ORGANIZATION> Vishnu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lintel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, based in suburban <LOCATION> Evanston </LOCATION>. The institute announced Monday it would return the lintel to <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> in exchange for a Thai artifact `` of equal artistic merit'' to be donated by the Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Elizabeth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cheney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a philanthropic group that wanted to help resolve the dispute. The lintel, a 2-by-3 foot stone crosspiece designed to fit above a door or window, depicts the Hindu god Vishnu reclining on water. It dates to <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s Khmer dynasty from A.D. 805-1250. It disappeared from the Phnom Rung temple, a national monument in northeastern <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> during the 1960s, <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> officials say. The lintel was first displayed at the institute 21 years ago. But museum officials said they did not learn until February that the <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> government wanted it returned for the temple's restoration. Thai demonstrators protested outside the museum earlier this year, hoping to have the lintel returned in time for reopening ceremonies at the Thai temple in May. Museum spokeswoman <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Voedisch </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> officials had been told of the decision to return the lintel, but she did not think an official response had been received by the institute. Monday's announcement came a day before a Thai representative and others demanding the lintel were scheduled to testify at a <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> committee meeting, <PERSON> Lapcharoensap </PERSON> said. He said the meeting would be held today despite the announcement. <PERSON> Lapcharoensap </PERSON> said the institute had said earlier it wanted to return the lintel, but nothing was done. `` If I have some skepticism, it's justified,''' he said. The institute said it got the lintel from the Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Alsdorf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, which acquired it in 1967 through a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> art dealer. The institute said the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> dealer had purchased the carving from a dealer in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> in 1966, where it was offered for sale on the open market. The museum said it agreed to return the lintel, with the help of the <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> foundation, to `` resolve the stalemate in negotiations and maintain the positive relationship that existed between <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' `` We are pleased to resolve this issue,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, the institute's director. `` This solution meets our requirement for just compensation.'' Ms. <PERSON> Voedisch </PERSON> said museum and <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> foundation officials would have to agree on the piece to be donated in exchange for the lintel, and that a decision was expected soon. `` Upon receipt of this gift, the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> will relinquish all rights and title to the lintel and donate it to <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>,'' the museum said.
