<FIRST>r a PM-HarvardUnion     10-25 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harvard Union,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>NLRB Rejects Harvard's Claims On Union Vote Tactics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Union officials at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> celebrated after a judge dismissed the school's attempt to overturn a vote to form a 3,400-member union for technical and clerical workers. The Ivy League school, however, insisted it has done nothing wrong. In a harshly worded opinion Monday, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> administrative law judge rejected the university's claim that labor organizers illegally coerced `` yes'' votes through a coordinated campaign to assure that union supporters cast ballots. The judge, <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmatz </PERSON>, certified the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clerical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> as the winner of the May ballot. `` We feel great about it,'' union director <PERSON> Kristine </PERSON> <PERSON> Rondeau </PERSON> said. `` We knew we were right, but we always were cautious about predicting the inevitability of our win.'' The union, an affiliate of the 1 million-member <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, won the election on a 1,530-1 ,486 vote in which more than 90 percent of eligible workers cast ballots `` The allegations do not suggest that the election was beclouded by threats, violence, vandalism, reprisals or the traditional forms of voter intimidation,'' <PERSON> Harmatz </PERSON> wrote. `` Indeed, none of the conduct subject to litigation in this proceeding would constitute an unfair labor practice.'' <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s brief in the case, <PERSON> Harmatz </PERSON> said, `` is replete with misinterpretations of the record'' of eight days of hearings the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> held in August on the university's charges. `` Because these references either are not supported by, or grossly overstate the proven facts, this decision seeks to, at this level, bring a halt to this approach,'' the judge said. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> Heffron </PERSON> said no decision has been made on whether to appeal <PERSON> Harmatz </PERSON>'s ruling to the full five-member board. Under the law, it has two weeks to file an appeal. `` The university's position is sound, and the union acted improperly,'' <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> Vice President for Finance <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said in a statement. `` It is plain that the opinion -LRB- by <PERSON> Harmatz </PERSON> -RRB- does not accurately reflect the record of the hearings in many respects.'' The union drive, which began in 1975, and the university's challenge had been viewed by several labor leaders as a major test of their ability to organize educated, white - and gray-collar technical workers who are assuming a greater proportion of the <ORGANIZATION> AFSCME </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> McEntee </PERSON> said Monday that the election, and the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> action upholding the results, was crucial for <ORGANIZATION> AFSCME </ORGANIZATION> and as `` a test case for the labor movement as a whole.'' `` The issues raised in this campaign were the issues that affect the workforce of today and tomorrow _ job and family issues that include affordable, quality child care, decent pensions and benefits and flexibility in hours of work,'' he said. In the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> hearings, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> alleged that union organizers harassed employees about voting, checked names of employees off a master list of supporters, paid airline tickets for vacationing workers to return to <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> to vote and `` systematically interrogated'' workers on their intentions. <PERSON> Harmatz </PERSON> said the allegations concerned `` a perfectly legitimate, apparently successful, tactical maneuver'' by the union to win maximum support. The university ran its own aggressive campaign against unionization that included appeals from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Bok </PERSON>.
