<HEAD>Curfew In Capital, Bomb Toll Rises To 8; Police Charge Protesters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with police charging
protesters. Raises bomb's death toll to eight. Picks up 9th graf
pvs, `Police said...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A strict curfew confined most residents of this capital to their homes today while, elsewhere on the island, police fired tear gas and charged with batons into thousands of anti-government demonstrators. Authorities imposed the curfew in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> and surrounding areas after a bomb killed eight people Monday at governing party meeting in the capital. They said the move was necessary because of reports the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, an extremist Sinhalese group, was planning an all-day strike The government said it feared a strike would trigger more violence. Police initially blamed the front for the Monday night bombing at a <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> home where members of President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, also predominantly Sinhalese, were meeting. But party officials said today they had not ruled out the possibility the bomb was the work of opposition political parties. Violence has escalated with the approach of presidential elections scheduled for Dec. 19. The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> has accused the Sinhalese-dominated government of making too many concessions to the Tamil ethnic minority seeking a separate homeland in northern and eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. In the town of <LOCATION> Medawachchiya </LOCATION>, about 90 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, police today dispersed 3,000 protesters, including many <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks and schoolchildren demanding the government's resignation In <LOCATION> Welimada </LOCATION>, about 70 miles east of the capital, about 5,000 people sat down on public highways and refused to move, officials said. Police were unable to disperse them, officials said. There were no immediate reports of injuries in the protests. Police at <ORGANIZATION> Colombo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> said the death toll in the bombing Monday rose to eight after three more people died of their wounds today. At least 40 others were injured, they added. Police said two men on a motorcycle flung two pipes packed with explosives into the crowd at <LOCATION> Kotehena </LOCATION>, 2 miles north of the city center, but only one of the bombs exploded. The victims have not been identified, because the curfew prevented relatives from going to the hospital morgue to view the remains. But preliminary reports by police indicated most of the dead and the most seriously injured were local members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The curfew was imposed at midnight Monday and was to remain in effect until 6 p.m. today. A senior <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> would meet in emergency session later today to decide whether to extend it. Streets in the capital were virtually deserted during the day. Police passes were required for anyone desiring to leave home, except for people seeking to buy food at shops near their homes, according to authorities. The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> has put up posters in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> and other parts of the country demanding <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>'s resignation, abrogation of a peace accord aimed at ending the Tamil revolt, and the withdrawal of 47,000 Indian soldiers deployed in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> to enforce the accord. Under the Indian-brokered accord, Tamils were to receive a measure of autonomy if Tamil rebels surrendered their arms and stopped attacking Sri Lankan troops and Sinhalese civilians. The rebels refused and have been battling the Indian peacekeepers for more than a year. Tamils comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. They claim they are discriminated against in employment, education and through use of the Sinhalese language. Sinhalese, who account for 75 percent of the population, control most top government and military posts. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved in the internal affairs of its island neighbor because of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s role as a regional power and the political clout of its own Tamil minority of 60 million.
