<HEAD>Man Loses Suit Because He Failed To Wear Seatbelt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMM, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man paralyzed from the waist down when his parked car was rammed by another vehicle has lost a lawsuit because he was not wearing a seat belt when he was injured. `` The ruling was a one-time decision due to the insurance policy clause which mandates wearing a seat belt even if the car is parked and the motor off. It does not apply to the overall seat belt law,'' <PERSON> Hamm </PERSON> court spokesman <PERSON> Karl-Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Heugemann </PERSON> said today. West German law requires all passengers in private cars to wear seat belts when the motor is running. <PERSON> Heugemann </PERSON> said the court decision only involved special daily insurance payments to the injured man during his stay in the hospital, `` which amounted to about 5,000 marks -LRB- $ 2,777 -RRB-.'' His hospital and medical care payments were not affected by the insurance clause, said <PERSON> Heugemann </PERSON>. <PERSON> Heugemann </PERSON> said the man was paralyzed in an accident at a service station while he was waiting in his parked car with the motor off. `` He was n't wearing a seat belt, and another vehicle hit his car while he was waiting for the service station to open,'' said <PERSON> Heugemann </PERSON>. He declined to provide the name of the man involved in the case, or say when he was injured.
