<HEAD>Yerkes Establishes Sperm Bank For Chimpanzees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's first sperm bank for chimpanzees is designed to meet the increasing demand for animals by AIDS researchers, the bank's founder says. Chimpanzees are highly valued in research because they are the closest biologically to humans. But they are a threatened species that can no longer be captured legally in the wild. Dr. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>, chief of reproductive biology at the <ORGANIZATION> Yerkes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Primate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said researchers there and at other centers around the world infect the animals with AIDS to study the progress of the disease in an animal with an immune system similar to man's. Unlike man, the animals do not die of acquired immune deficiency syndrome, but they can spread the virus and therefore are not allowed to breed after being infected. `` I'm glad to hear about his success,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kraemer </PERSON>, a specialist in primate reproduction and a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor. `` It's important that we develop techniques for sperm storage and artificial insemination for a number of species.'' The bank will help breeders maintain a genetically diverse population of captive chimps and give scientists a model for developing sperm banks for other primates such as gorillas. For more than three decades, scientists have frozen human and cattle sperm successfully, but the same formulas did not prevent ice crystals from destroying the chimpanzee sperm until <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>'s success <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> began freezing the chimpanzee sperm in 1986, and eventually found that it had to be frozen more slowly than that of other species.
