<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today demanded an immediate meeting with <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> to prepare the way for the convening Friday of talks with the opposition on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s future. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> rejected the demand, leaving prospects for the start to the round-table talks in doubt. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> must meet Wednesday to clear away disputes on who can participate in the talks. The government objects to two names proposed by Solidarity and wants clarification on whether the individuals will respect <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s constitutional order, he said. The talks can not begin without such a preparatory meeting, Urban told reporters at his weekly news conference. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> later reiterated that he would reject any governent interference in the composition of Solidarity's delegation to the talks. He said he does not want another preparatory meeting with <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>. The two men have met three times since Aug. 31. `` I will not allow any personnel changes. It could be a precedent, a dangerous precedent for the future,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. He said church mediator <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Stelmachowski </PERSON> was fully empowered to negotiate any other procedural or technical matters on his behalf. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who spoke by telephone from his home in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, said he still hoped for discussions that would bring about `` understanding and the implementation of pluralism,'' and said the proposed date of Friday was acceptable to him for the talks to begin. Urban charged that Solidarity's `` stubbornness'' was preventing the talks from beginning. Urban's remarks today were the first time the government has announced a proposed date for the round-table talks. <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> agreed to such talks Aug. 31 while strikes continued around <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in the country's worst labor unrest in seven years. After begin guaranteed the talks could include the subject of Solidarity's future, as well as broader questions of economic and political pluralism in the communist country, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> ended the strikes. The opposition demands the talks lead to legalization of Solidarity, banned in 1982 after the December 1981 martial law crackdown. Solidarity had been the first recognized independent labor federation in the Soviet bloc. On Friday, Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said the government opposes legalizing Solidarity until the economy improves and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> changes its political system to allow more political demands outside of trade unions.
