<HEAD>Reagan Ups Ante in Diplomatic Tiff with Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> diplomats and other officials will be denied visas to enter the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> under a proclamation signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the White House announced today. The action is another step in the diplomatic conflict between the Sandinista government and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, which dates back to July 11, when <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> expelled <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> and seven other diplomats. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> retaliated the next day by expelling <LOCATION> Nicaraguan </LOCATION> ambassador <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Tunnermann </PERSON> and seven others. Since then, the Sandinista government has not acted on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attempts to replace the expelled <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoy to the Central American nation. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in his proclamation, says he found `` the unrestricted ... entry of officers and employees of the Nicaraguan government and the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> ... to be detrimental to the interests of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk pointed out that the presidential action comes not only in the wake of the July explusions, but also in light of further restrictions placed on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. `` We've been trying to get our people replaced, and we have n't gotten anywhere,'' <PERSON> Popadiuk </PERSON> said He noted that on Sept. 22, the Sandinista government required that American diplomats based in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> who leave the country, for whatever reason, must wait three weeks before they are allowed to re-enter <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. At the time, the administration said it would take some type of retaliatory action, but did not state what it would be. Diplomats already posted to the Nicaraguan embassy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are unaffected by the proclamation. Officials assigned now or in the future to the Nicaraguan <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mission in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> or the mission to the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are also unaffected.
