<HEAD>Proxmire's Successor: Millionaire Businessman or Female State
Senator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EGGLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Millionaire businessman <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> won <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> primary in the face of charges he was buying the election with personal wealth _ a far cry from the penny-pinching campaigns of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, the man he hopes to succeed. In the most recent general election polling, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> also has been leading the Republican nominee, state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Engeleiter </PERSON>. But <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> officials say she still can win, and an appearance by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on her behalf has been promised before the election. <PERSON> Engeleiter </PERSON>, 36, of <LOCATION> Brookfield </LOCATION>, would be the first woman <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> has sent to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. She also would be the younger than any current member of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Whoever wins, the battle has ended a tradition of low-cost campaigns that <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> established in his 31 years in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The retirement of <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, who will turn 73 three days after the election, also ends an era of statewide, personal campaigning that spurned the use of paid advertising. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, often focused on issues of what he saw as government waste during his long political career. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, 53, of <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, already has set a record for election spending in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, contributing $ 3.84 million of his own money to his first try at public office. His campaign ha