<FIRST>r w AM-NewDrug     10-25 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Drug,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Approves New Drug For Treatment of Cancer-Related Diarrhea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Food and <ORGANIZATION> Drugs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday approved a new drug for controlling a type of diarrhea that often kills patients with intestinal cancer. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the new drug, called octreotide acetate, `` can dramatically improve the life'' of patients with malignant carcinoid tumors and vasoactive intestinal peptide-secreting tumors. These cancers grow slowly and often are not diagnosed until after they have spread and become inoperable. The malignancies themselves often are not fatal for up to 20 years, but they cause a severe and frequent diarrhea that can cripple and even kill. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the new drug will permit many patients with the intestinal cancer to live normal lives `` rather than be weakened and continually hospitalized.'' `` For many, it will reduce or eliminate the frequent and devastating bouts of diarrhea that often require repeated hospitalizations for intravenous fluid replacement therapy,'' he said. About one or two people per million in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> develop the intestinal cancer annually. The cancer often goes undiagnosed for seven or eight years. Though patients can live with the cancer for years, it causes heavy secretions of peptides, a type of protein which triggers severe and unrelenting diarrhea, along with wheezing, heart problems and loss of energy. The new drug does not attack the cancer, but controls secretion of the peptides. The drug mimics the action of somatostatine, a naturally occurring hormone that regulates secretions by the organs in the body, and prevents excess release of the peptides. This, in turn, eliminates the cause of the diarrhea. Officials said the drug is administered by injection. It was developed in the <ORGANIZATION> Sandoz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> laboratories in <LOCATION> Basel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, and approved by the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> after major clinical trials in this country. It will be marketed under the name <PERSON> Sandostatin </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said that since some patients on the drug developed gallstones, ultrasonic monitoring of patients is recommended.
</TEXT>
