 A proposed amendment to the city charter that would ban discrimination against homosexuals has pitted conservative clergymen against a coalition of advocates for civil liberties and gay rights. The proposal on the Nov. 8 ballot would prohibit discrimination in jobs, housing or public accommodations because of sexual orientation. `` We believe discrimination is fundamentally wrong. It goes against the health and well-being of our entire community,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, a proponent of the amendment, said in a statement. Opponents argue that anti-discrimination laws should not apply to homosexuality because it is a chosen lifestyle. Others have called homosexuality a `` perversion'' and have prominently mentioned acquired immune deficiency syndrome, for which sexually active gay men are at high risk. One minister who opposes the measure has threatened to go on radio and television if the amendment is approved and declare that the northern <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> city is the place for homosexuals to be. The Rev. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> said his congregation, the <ORGANIZATION> LaPorte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>, has pledged to spend $ 4,000 to defeat the amendment. Last week, he began criticizing the proposal in a series of paid, two-hour radio broadcasts on a local station that prompted a flurry of angry calls from listeners. He also plans to buy time on a local cable television. `` I'm going to go on my program and let the homosexuals around the nation know that <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> is the place to come to'' if the amendment is passed, said <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>. Other clergymen, however, have spoken out in favor of the proposal. Its supporters are conducting a low-key,