<HEAD>Teen Suicides In Cobb Focus Of CDC Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The suicides of 14 Cobb County teen-agers in a 25-month period has triggered a study on teen suicide by the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> and the county health department. Dr. <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Mork </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Cobb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, said the goal of the effort is to produce the first detailed study of suicide based on interviews with those who survive attempts to kill themselves. `` We've got this glaring problem of people killing themselves. We want to know why,'' she said. `` Who are they? What are they like? Are their parents middle-class? How old are they? If they are in school, what school do they go to? What method do they choose?'' The study, now encompassing 441 case studies of all ages, indicates at least 900 people may attempt suicide in <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> every year. The county, which borders northwest <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, has about 300,000 residents. Fourteen adolescents 19 or younger killed themselves in <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> from September 1986 to October 1988. The county's suicide rate _ 14.7 deaths for every 100,000 people _ is almost three deaths higher than the state average and almost two higher than the national average. Dr. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Carroll </PERSON> of the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Cobb </ORGANIZATION> study may offer insights into the rising number of suicides. Researchers eventually want to study 1,000 cases. Interviews with 441 patients between October 1987 and October 1988 show: _ Only 38 of the 441 who attempted suicide took precautions to avoid rescue, a much smaller proportion than those who succeed in committing suicide _ More than 240 of the 441 took drug overdoses, while few who succeed in committing suicide take drugs Most use guns or hang themselves. _ More than 60 percent were women, but women constituted only one-third of those who succeed _ About 254 of the 441 expressed an intent to commit suicide, either in a note or conversation According to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>, suicide rates are climbing for teens and adults. The overall national rate has risen from 11.9 suicides for every 100,000 people in 1980 to 12.8 in 1986. The death toll has risen from 26,869 to 30,904 during the same six-year period.
