<HEAD>Orders Down 4.1 Percent Last Month</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS last graf to show shipments fell in September, rose
in August</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Orders to factories for `` big ticket'' durable goods dropped 4.1 percent in September, pulled down by sharp declines in the volatile defense and transportation sectors, the government said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said total orders fell $ 5.0 billion to a seasonally adjusted $ 117.7 billion last month. The steep decline follows a big 5.7 percent increase in August and a 7.4 percent drop in July, the worst monthly decline in four years. The durable goods total, which includes manufactured goods ranging from household appliances to huge airliners, has been buffeted up and down in recent months by wide swings in orders for aircraft, ships and tanks, affecting both the transportation and military sectors. Orders for transportation equipment in September were down 10.2 percent to $ 31.2 billion, following an 18.6 percent jump in August and a 22.5 percent plummet in July. Aircraft and shipbuilding pulled the category down last month. Orders for defense goods fell 12.3 percent to $ 7.0 billion last month, following a 14.7 percent rise in August and a 49.4 percent drop in July. Excluding defense, orders fell 3.5 percent in September, rose 5.1 percent in August and fell 2.2 percent in July. Excluding transportation, orders were down 1.7 percent last month, following a 1.3 percent rise and a 1.0 percent fall. However, the weakness was widespread in September. Electrical machinery was down 4.1 percent, the second consecutive monthly decline, while non-electrical machinery dropped 7.5 percent. The key category of non-defense capital goods, considered a good barometer for business expansion plans, fell 11.9 percent to $ 34.1 billion, the steepest retreat since January 1986. But, it followed increases of 6.9 percent in August and 2.1 percent a month before that. The widespread weakness fits in with economists' view that the momentum of economic growth slowed as the third quarter was ending. Manufacturing, driven by strong export sales, has been one of the strongest sectors of the economy this year. Analysts disagree over whether the slowing in the third quarter represents the beginning of a decline or a temporary pause. The only area of strength in September was in primary metals, which includes steel. It rose 6.5 percent, following declines of 2.0 percent in August and 1.4 percent in July. Shipments of durable goods fell 0.8 percent last month to $ 116.9 billion, following a 4.2 percent rise in August.
