<HEAD>Orders For Big Ticket Goods Plunge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AP LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government reported Monday that orders for `` big ticket'' durable goods plunged 4.1 percent in September, but economists are reluctant to conclude that the red-hot manufacturing boom is ending. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said total orders fell $ 5.0 billion to a seasonally adjusted $ 117.7 billion last month, pulled down by dramatic declines in the volatile defense and transportation sectors. Other categories, including machinery, computers and capital goods purchased by businesses, also fell. The latest report fits in with other signs of a slowdown last month, including the second consecutive decline in retail sales and a drop in manufacturing employment. But analysts said it was too soon to declare that manufacturing, which has driven robust economic growth this year, is slowing significantly. A boom in export sales, fueled by the lower value of the dollar, has kept factories humming. Manufacturers in turn have invested heavily to expand the capacity of their plants, spurring the fastest growth in capital spending since 1984. `` There are some cautionary notes in this report, but even so the economy is still very strong. The manufacturing sector is n't faltering just because orders went down one month,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> He noted that unusually wide swings in orders for both transportation equipment and military goods have pushed the overall orders number up and down over the last four months. Durable goods, items expected to last three or more years, include a wide range of manufactured items, from refrigerators and other household appliances to large computers and battleships. Orders had jumped 5.7 percent in August, plummeted 7.4 percent in July and soared 8.7 percent in June. Orders for transportation equipment in September were down 10.2 percent, following an 18.6 percent jump in August, while orders for defense goods fell 12.3 percent last month, following a 14.7 percent rise. Excluding defense, orders fell 3.5 percent in September. Excluding transportation, orders were down 1.7 percent. The key category of non-defense capital goods, considered a good barometer for business expansion plans, fell 11.9 percent. It was the first decline since May and the steepest retreat since January 1986. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Annable </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, said the decline in capital goods orders was `` disquieting because it suggests a weakening in the primary engine of economic growth.'' However, he said manufacturing profits are high and factories are using a high percentage of their capacity, suggesting that capital goods orders will rebound in the months ahead. Electrical machinery also fell in September, by 4.1 percent, the second consecutive monthly decline, while non-electrical machinery dropped 7.5 percent. The only area of strength in September was in primary metals, which includes steel. It rose 6.5 percent, following declines of 2.0 percent in August and 1.4 percent in July. Shipments of durable goods fell 0.8 percent in September to $ 116.9 billion, following a 4.2 percent increase in August. The backlog of unfilled orders expanded by a modest 0.2 percent to $ 431.9 billion last month after three strong gains from June through August. In a separate report Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of existing single-family homes fell 2.2 percent in September. It was only the second decline since January.
