<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year after Rep. <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> nearly died of breathing problems, a rare transplant has given him new lungs and a renewed shot for a 10th term in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Five months after he underwent the double-lung transplant, however, <PERSON> Spence </PERSON>'s health remains a central issue in his re-election campaign. The 60-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Lexington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> faces a challenge from <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> banker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leventis </PERSON> and has recently begun to step up his campaigning. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON>'s surgeon and colleagues say the congressman has made a strong recovery from the sometimes-fatal operation. For six months, while he waited for a lung transplant after being diagnosed with chronic obstructive lung disease, <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> moved about in a wheelchair aided by portable oxygen. Others worried about his future. `` Before his operation, he was having trouble breathing,'' said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Fant </PERSON>, spokesman for Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Spratt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, who serves with <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> on the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was pretty obvious he was having trouble speaking. He was wheezing and coughing a lot and he looked bad.'' In May, the wait ended, and doctors at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> successfully transplanted the lungs of an 18-year-old <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> motorcycle accident victim into <PERSON> Spence </PERSON>. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> spent the next few months learning to walk and to hold his head erect again, before being