<TEXT>
 A top state department official said Tuesday he was encouraged by the outcome of talks in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last week in which Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials recommended that `` immediate measures'' be taken to halt overfishing for pollock in the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, the department's ambassador for oceans and fisheries who led the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation, also said that both countries are `` increasingly concerned'' about reports of possible illegal salmon fishing by the Japanese and the Taiwanese in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and agreed to cooperate in enforcement activities. `` The Soviets are equally as concerned about possible illegal salmon fishing as we are,'' <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> said in an interview. `` All of these things are related because they all deal with <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> fishing.'' <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> said he was `` quite satisfied'' with the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> talks and he expected a plan for managing pollock stocks in the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> to emerge from another round of talks either late this year or in early 1989. In a joint statement, negotiators meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> said scientists from both countries agreed that unregulated fishing was `` clearly detrimental'' to pollock stocks in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet zones that surround the international portion of the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. `` In light of the urgent nature of this problem, the two delegations agreed that ... immediate measures are necessary to conserve fishery resources throughout the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> ecosystem,'' the statement said. The statement gave no indication what measures the two countries might consider to halt