<HEAD>Existing-Home Sales Down 2.2 Percent in September</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite a housing boom in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, sales of existing homes fell 2.2 percent in September after a surprisingly strong summer, a real estate trade group said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of existing homes declined to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.63 million units last month, following a 2.2 percent increase in August. But last month's level was still higher than most economists would have predicted this spring, when mortgage interest rates began to creep higher. Fixed-rate mortgages on average hit a low of 9.84 percent in February and rose to 10.71 percent by early August. Since then, they have eased back to 10.28 percent, but many analysts expect them to start rising again by year's end. Existing-home sales in the late spring and early summer were strong, in part because many buyers apparently purchased homes sooner than planned in an attempt to beat rising interest rates. `` The decline ... in September is a hangover from the buying spree of the summer,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON>, chief economist of the Realtors. `` The extraordinary increase'' of the summer was `` in part borrowed from September.'' <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON> predicted sales rates will continue to lag in the fourth quarter and by year's end would total 3.47 million units, down only slightly from 3.53 million in 1987. The West was the only region of the nation showing an increase of sales last month. They rose 6.0 percent to an annual rate of 710,000 units, the highest level since December 1986, following a 3.1 percent increase in August. Sales fell 5.8 percent in the <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> to 650,000 units on an annual basis, the lowest since January. They fell 3.2 percent in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> to 900,000 units and were off 2.8 percent in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> to 1.38 million units. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Savacool </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a forecasting firm in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s strong economy and growing population are supporting the housing market. `` People have been moving into <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in droves, and that provides a lot of support for the housing market there even though the rest of the nation looks weak,'' <PERSON> Savacool </PERSON> said. He noted that 400,000 people moved to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> last year, more than to any other state. The main reason for sluggish sales in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> is high prices, he said. Over the past year, existing-home prices have risen most steeply in the West. The median was $ 124,300 in September, up 7.1 percent. However, the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> remained the most costly area with a median of $ 141,400, up 6.3 percent from a year earlier. The median in the South was $ 82,400, up 3.6 percent from September 1987. In the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, the price was $ 67,100, up 1.5 percent. The national appreciation rate over 12 months was 3.5 percent to a median of $ 88,500, meaning half of the homes sold for more and half for less.
