<HEAD>47 New Heart Drugs In Works</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that 47 of its members companies are working on a total of 87 new drugs for cardiovascular diseases, including heart disease, hypertension and stroke. `` No other disease is targeted by so many drugs in development or so much investment in research,'' said association president <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mossinghoff </PERSON>. Each of the 87 drugs is either in human clinical trials or awaiting final approval by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. He acknowledged at a news conference that one of the reasons the companies are pouring so much investment into cardiovascular diseases is that there remains a huge market for such therapies even though doctors now realize they are among the most preventable illnesses for people who adopt healthy lifestyles in their early and middle years. Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beary </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, senior vice president for science and technology for the trade association, noted that heart disease remains the nation's No. 1 killer and stroke No. 3. Even though the population is generally healthier, as well as older, than in years past, <PERSON> Beary </PERSON> said, `` At some point these diseases catch up with everyone.'' The <ORGANIZATION> PMA </ORGANIZATION> survey of its more than 100 members was designed to provide an overview of the scope of new drug development in various categories, rather than highlight any particularly promising `` breakthrough'' drugs. In fact, there are already a number of drugs on the market for cardiovascular diseases _ unlike for many other diseases that afflict mostly the elderly, such as Alzheimer's. <PERSON> Mossinghoff </PERSON> acknowledged that `` a subliminal purpose -LRB- for the press conference -RRB- is to let elder <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> know that it is important for the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> to have adequate funding'' to review these new drugs. `` This puts a little bit of pressure on the system,'' he said. <PERSON> Mossinghoff </PERSON> said it is likely some of the companies developing new cardiovascular disease drugs will take advantage of new <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> guidelines announced last week that holds out the prospect of quicker approval of new drugs if companies work closely with the agency in early clinical trials and make a larger research investment to accumulate more test data earlier than is often the current practice. The trade association plans similar surveys in December for cancer drugs under development and in January for arthritis, Alzheimer's and other aging diseases. The cardiovascular disease survey found more medicines being developed for hypertension, or high blood pressure, than any other condition with all but three of the 38 drugs in that category in the final stages of testing. The <ORGANIZATION> PMA </ORGANIZATION> said the second largest category is congestive heart failure, the final and often fatal phase of heart disease, with 28 drugs under development.
