<HEAD>Perez de Cuellar Invites Iran, Iraq to Resume Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> on Tuesday invited <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to resume their peace talks, and members of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> called on the nations to be more cooperative in the new talks. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said his invitation to resume talks on Monday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> has been sent, but it was too early for a reply. Officials of both countries had expressed their willingness to resume talks before the end of the month in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> gave the members of the council a report Tuesday that brought out the urgency of a rapid troop withdrawal from the Iran-Iraq border, said the council's president, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Count </PERSON> <PERSON> York </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Wartenburg </PERSON>. The 15 Security Council members unanimously adopted a statement expressing their concern over the slow pace of the talks in September and early October, he said. The members `` express their expectation that substantive progress will be made in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in order to achieve a full and rapid implementation of Resolution 598 as an integral whole,'' said <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Wartenburg </PERSON>, referring to the council's peace plan. Observers interpreted the stress on implementing Resolution 598 as an `` integral whole'' as pressure on <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to give up its insistence that the <LOCATION> Shatt-al-Arab </LOCATION> waterway that form the southern border between the two nations must be cleared before the peace talks take up other issues. The waterway is <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s only navigable outlet to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, but it has been clogged with sunken ships and silt since the war broke out in 1980. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said that he and his special mediator for the talks, Swedish Ambassador <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliasson </PERSON>, will go to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, but the secretary-general expects to stay only for four or five days. `` I am encouraged by the fact that both sides appear ready to show their goodwill by proceeding with some repatraition -LRB- of prisoners of war -RRB- in the near future,'' he said. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has suggested that all POWs could be sent home as a humanitarian gesture outside of the peace negotiations. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said the POW issue is one of the terms of the resolution and can not be separated from it, but Iranian Ambassador <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ja'afar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> said last week his country is ready to reciprocate humanitarian gestures. <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> suggested that sick and injured prisoners and those held the longest might be the first to be repatriated. Iranian and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> sources have said both sides have accepted a compromise from the secretary-general to break the stalemate over the Shatt-al-Arab by postponing discussions of the issue until a later stage of the talks. The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has accepted <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s demand to stop searching ships for war material bound for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The compromises would allow both sides to concentrate on negotiating the withdrawal of their troops to an internationally recognized border and the repatriation of POWs. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has not stopped any ships since Aug. 20, the day the U.N.-mediated cease-fire began.
