<HEAD>Black Harvard Faculty, Administrators Call For Greater Affirmative
Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IAN DONNIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> can not foster the ideal of racial equality given the underrepresentation of blacks among its faculty and administrators, says a report issued Tuesday by an organization of black staffers. Blacks make up 3 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Ivy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> school's instructors and administrators, and the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Faculty </ORGANIZATION> and Administrators called for increasing that figure to 10 percent. `` The challenge of overcoming the attachment to the beliefs and benefits of white supremacy remains,'' the association said in its report. The authors of the paper, titled `` The Final Report,'' used an unusual story-telling technique, hypothesizing what would happen if <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Bok </PERSON> and all of the school's black faculty and administrators were killed in an explosion. The outpouring of sympathy, they concluded, would mean that <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> `` would adopt a much more effective program for recruiting blacks to the school than now exists.'' <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, assistant dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Design </ORGANIZATION> and an association co-chair, said framing the report this way was intended to dramatize the group's message. `` The use of stories to make a point is a well-known African tradition, one that is increasingly used as a medium for scholarly discourse,'' <PERSON> Watson </PERSON> said. `` It is our hope that the report's unusual character will prevent its becoming another forgotten report on affirmative action, a subject about which much more has been written than accomplished.'' The association said 17 of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s present 957 tenured faculty, or 1.8 percent, are black. Twenty-six of the 2,265 tenure-line faculty, or 1.1. percent, are black, and 155 of 3,205 administrators, or 4.8 percent, are black, it said In the imaginary scenario, an unnamed president would increase minority hiring by vigorous effort and, when those positions could not be filled, fund fellowships to help promising black students gain the credentials to teach at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> or other elite schools. `` We view this report as an incentive for a more detailed discussion and review with the deans of the university's 1988 Affirmative Action Plan,'' said association co-chair <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> professor. In noting that release of `` The Final Report'' comes 100 years after black educator and historian W.E.B. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Bois </PERSON>' admission to <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, the association said blacks still face prejudice at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>. `` The association's report noted that today, Dr. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Bois </PERSON> would find a substantial number of black students at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>. Most are spared the overt hostility that barred <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Bois </PERSON> from every social activity except the philosophy club. `` Even so, contemporary black students encounter color-based discrimination in many subtle and debilitating forms, and they suffer the no-less hurtful slights and disparaging assumptions about their abilities that <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Bois </PERSON> endured,'' it said.
