<HEAD>New Handbook Tries to Put Order Into the Night</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new 45-page handbook governing <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s bustling nightclubs has been adopted by the city's <ORGANIZATION> Licensing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, with provisions including bans on discriminatory admission practices and display of `` improper'' material. While some of the rules are good ideas, the restriction about what can be displayed could interfere with owners' rights to free expression, one civil liberties advocate said. <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s bustling and sometimes rowdy night scene prompted officials to draw up the compilation of rules and regulations, <ORGANIZATION> Licensing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairwoman <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Gargiulo </PERSON> said Tuesday. The handbook, which clubs will be required to show to patrons on request, is easier to read than the fine print regulations on individual licenses issued to owners and will fit into police officers' pockets, Ms. <PERSON> Gargiulo </PERSON> said. The new rules prohibit signs such as `` Proper Dress Required,'' a vague stipulation that sometimes led to selective discrimination, Ms. <PERSON> Gargiulo </PERSON> said. Also banned are VIP passes on any basis that `` invidiously discriminates.'' `` We had cases where a white male with no tie was allowed in and a black male was told at the door that he could n't come in without a tie,'' Ms. <PERSON> Gargiulo </PERSON> said. `` We do n't want to leave it up to the doorman.'' New signs will have to spell out what constitutes proper dress, such as jacket and tie required for men, she said. Other new rules require that bouncers not strike customers unless hit first and makes nightclub owners responsible for the actions of valet parking companies they may hire. Waiting lines at popular nightspots will have to be limited and supervised. Penalties for violations include a wide variety of license restrictions, ranging from limits on the hours liquor can be served to outright suspension of a club's license. The ban on displaying material of an `` improper or objectionable nature'' in clubs outside the Combat Zone, the adult entertainment district, came under criticism from the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. `` This is kind of a classic, so-called obscenity issue,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, the organization's executive director. `` We know that in this society, standards obviously differ between what's acceptable and not acceptable Somehow, female nudity in a lot of places is just sort of accepted, but now males is not.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinstein </PERSON>, a lawyer with the <ORGANIZATION> CLU </ORGANIZATION>, said the ban on improper material could be difficult to enforce. `` If I'm a restaurant owner with a statue of <PERSON> Michelangelo </PERSON>'s <PERSON> David </PERSON> in my place, is that covered because it's nudity?'' he said. Ms. <PERSON> Gargiulo </PERSON> said the rule is not intended to ban nude prints that hang inside some restaurants, but is aimed at material that is `` way out of line.'' The guideline on objectionable material will be whether it would be deemed unsuitable for view by members of the public if it were located in areas such as public parks or government and business offices. Enforcing the rules may be difficult, but not impossible, Ms. <PERSON> Gargiulo </PERSON> said. `` They're very subjective and that's why we hold hearings.''
</TEXT>
