<HEAD>Builders' Group Say Energy Efficient Homes Won't Add to Radon
Buildup</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new 2nd graf to RESTORE dropped matter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A major builders' association on Tuesday said it has found no evidence that energy-efficient homes increase radon concentrations and that it is advising its members to build homes as tight as possible. `` Our practices recommend good air sealing techniques,'' just as would be used in trying to save energy, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Spears </PERSON>, program manager for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which is affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Some analysts have suggested that the increasing importance being placed on energy efficiency also may be increasing the tendency of radon, an odorless, radioactive gas given off by all soils, to concentrate indoors. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has warned that although increased ventilation may help particular radon-rich homes, as a general rule well-ventilated homes appear to have no exemption from radon buildup. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates that radon could be causing as many as 20,000 deaths from lung cancer each year. In September, the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> issued a national health advisory warning of radon dangers and the two agencies urged testing of every home where people live on the second floor or below. As for home sealing, `` We're finding it has little to do with radon,'' <PERSON> Spears </PERSON> said at a news conference. As a result, the association is recommending `` the same practices we have recommended for years for energy conservation. In fact, we've found that energy conservation has little to do with radon concentration in the house. We've measured houses all over the country.'' The association recommended many techniques for reducing radon buildup, such as carefully sealing off the basement _ often the same techniques used for keeping water out. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ethier </PERSON>, litigation counsel for the association, said members were being advised that `` if they make a reasoned judgment that there may be high radon levels,'' that they should `` rough in'' mitigation techniques such as under-slab ventilation pipes that may be ignored later if appropriate, or connected to a fan to divert radon-laden air around the basement. In states such as <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> with well-publicized instances of radon buildup, <PERSON> Ethier </PERSON> said he has found `` universal'' adoption of such precautions by builders. Builders report that the techniques may add as little as $ 100 to the cost of a home, if water barriers are already being used, but as much as $ 600 if they are not, he said.
