<SECOND>AM-Gulf-Oil,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Largest Iranian Oil Port To Be Opened To Foreign Ships</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> will open its main oil port to foreign vessels as it pulls its own tankers out of service from the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> route heavily attacked during its war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, shipping sources said Tuesday. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> will eliminate service by Iranian-operated tankers from <LOCATION> Kharg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in the northeastern gulf to the <LOCATION> Sirri </LOCATION> terminal in the south by the end of the year, according to the London-based <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION>, which monitors maritime traffic It quoted <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Souri </PERSON>, chairman and managing director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iranian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tanker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, as saying he expected foreign tankers to take over the transport of half of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s oil exports from <LOCATION> Kharg </LOCATION> within a month and all of it within two months. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> imposed an air and sea blockade around <LOCATION> Kharg </LOCATION> in 1984, a move that triggered the tanker war in which more than 500 ships were attacked by both countries. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is exporting an estimated 1.4 million barrels of oil a day. Officials have said they plan to increase their long-term export capacity to around 4.5 million barrels a day. The <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> report underlined Iranian efforts to restore normal oil export operations following the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the 8-year-old war between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Gulf-based shipping officials reported earlier this month the Iranians had st