 May. <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> said that disbanding <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s tanker service would save <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> an estimated $ 300 million a year. <LOCATION> Kharg </LOCATION> and its tankers were bombed scores of times by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s air force and the port was heavily fortified with anti-aircraft and missile batteries. The Iranians tried to circumvent the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> blockade by installing a makeshift terminal at <LOCATION> Sirri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, about 350 miles south. Foreign tankers loaded there until the Iraqis raided <LOCATION> Sirri </LOCATION> in 1986. Loading operations were then moved another 120 miles south to <LOCATION> Larak </LOCATION> island in the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, the gateway to the gulf. But Iraqi warplanes began hitting <PERSON> Larak </PERSON> as well, culminating in a May 14 strike in which several supertankers were sunk or crippled. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> severely damaged the Sirri platform on April 18 in retaliatory raids for the mining of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship. Since the cease-fire, <ORGANIZATION> Sirri </ORGANIZATION>'s terminal has reopened, shipping officials said, while <PERSON> Larak </PERSON> has ceased to function as an oil terminal.
