<FIRST>r a AM-DrugTesting     10-25 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Testing,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Court Rules Random Urine Testing of Elite Police Force Legal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Random urine testing for drugs among an elite corps of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> police officers is legal because of the dangerous and sensitive nature of their work, a divided <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state Court of Appeals ruled Tuesday. The 5-2 decision by the state's top court not only overturns two lower court rulings, it constitutes an `` about face'' for a court which only last year ruled that a drug-testing plan for <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> teachers was an unreasonable invasion of their privacy, the dissenting judges said. The court decision upholds <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s 1986 order that members of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Organized </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> must undergo random urinalysis for drugs Approximately 1,100 of the city's 27,000 police officers volunteer for duty in the special unit. Up to 90 percent are involved in narcotics-related work. `` The terror-filled world they are working in requires the sternest precautionary safeguards to weed out drug abusers from their own ranks,'' wrote Judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellacosa </PERSON> for the majority. The court ruled unanimously last year in a case involving <LOCATION> Patchogue </LOCATION> teachers that governments could n't force public employees to take drug tests unless there is a `` reasonable suspicion'' that workers are using drugs. Much of <PERSON> Bellacosa </PERSON>'s 14-page ruling was taken up with an explanation of why the police officers should be held to stricter standards than the teachers. The lower courts incorrectly gave an `` absolutist reading'' to the <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>' decision in the teachers' case, he said. The `` direct correlation'' between an organized crime officer's work and drugs should be considered in evaluating the extent of their constitutional rights to privacy, <PERSON> Bellacosa </PERSON> wrote `` The officers agree to undergo microscopic examinations of their personal lives, their financial affairs and their professional judgment calls,'' <PERSON> Bellacosa </PERSON> said. `` Realistically, the proposed random drug testing in these narrow circumstances is just another layer of an already heightened, persistent and employee-expected scrutiny.'' Judge <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON>, in a dissenting opinion, said the government has n't established why the testing is needed or why the officers should be held to such special standards. `` The public clearly has an interest in the integrity of every employee who serves it,'' <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> wrote. `` Equally clearly, that alone does not give the state the power to conduct intrusive searches of their person.'' According to court papers, all city police recruits are tested for drugs when they apply to the department, again during their five-month police academy training and at the end of their 18-month probation. Tenured officers are subject to testing if there's a reasonable suspicion of drug use. Officers applying to the organized crime unit were required by <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> in 1986 to sign a form acknowledging that periodic drug testing was a condition of employment. The policemen's union, the Patrolmen's <ORGANIZATION> Benevolent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, sued to overturn the order two days after it was announced. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerno </PERSON>, the union's lawyer, said he was surprised at the decision. He called the drug testing an `` excessive attempt'' to solve a problem that does n't really exist. The decision gives new life to municipalities who hope to start drug testing programs, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Adler </PERSON>, a lawyer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s corporation counsel's office. The city in late 1987 tried to institute random drug testing for all corrections officers, he said. But lower courts have struck down the program, citing the <LOCATION> Patchogue </LOCATION> case, he said. `` I think certainly those who might favor drug testing are probably better equipped to make a legal argument justifying the testing than they had before this decision came down,'' <PERSON> Adler </PERSON> said. According to police department records, narcotics-related disciplinary charges have been filed against 10 police officers in the crime unit in four years. <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> said these statistics show there's no indication of a drug abuse problem within this unit. `` The important goal of deterrence ... is not, without evidence of a pervasive problem among the persons to be tested, justification for this search,'' she said.
</TEXT>
