 The <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Discrimination </ORGANIZATION> has found that the 1985 firing of the only black coach in the <ORGANIZATION> Pittsfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Little </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> was racially motivated. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> filed a complaint with the state commission after he was dismissed as coach of the <ORGANIZATION> Connor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmacy </ORGANIZATION> team in June 1985 following a series of disputes with league officials. Among other things, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> contended that league Umpire-In-Chief <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Stannard </PERSON> had called him `` boy'' in a `` racially and personally derogatory manner in the course of a game.'' At the time, the league of six teams had no black players, according to the commission. Each team has at least one coach, all of whom serve for free, according to league Secretary-Treasurer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchesi </PERSON>. Following its finding, the state commission attempted to mediate the dispute between <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and the league, but no conclusion was reached in a three-hour meeting Monday, said <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON> <PERSON> Nevins </PERSON>, commission staff council. She said that if no agreement could be worked out privately between the parties, the commission could hold public hearings. After that the issue could be decided by the courts. The main sticking point, according to <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> was the wording of an apology he sought from league officials. He said that he had never sought monetary compensation from the league but wanted the apology to boost his chances of seeking other coaching jobs. `` If there is a statement to be issued,'' he said. `` I just want it to clarify that I'm not the troublemaker some people might make me out to be. This is n't a situation I created.'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, who works as a wireman at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, had previously coached junior varsity baseball at <ORGANIZATION> Lee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and junior varsity girls basketball at <ORGANIZATION> Taconic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsfield </LOCATION>. He had initially filed a civil suit against the league over his dismissal in 1985, but withdrew the action in favor of pursuing a complaint through the commission. `` I could n't afford to co through the courts,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. He said the cost of the complaint was about half that of a civil suit.
