<HEAD>Help Pours Into Hurricane-Hit Nicaragua; Death Toll At 123</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ruby, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> struggled Tuesday to recover from a hurricane that killed at least 60 people and left 300,000 homeless in this Central American nation. Help poured in from a dozen countries. Floods and strong winds heavily damaged crops throughout <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Hurricane Joan killed another 63 people elsewhere in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ 23 in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, four in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, 25 in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and 11 in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> _ before it crossed <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and was reborn Monday in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> as Tropical Storm <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON>. At 5 p.m. EDT Tuesday, an advisory from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> National Hurricane Center in <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said the storm had weakened to a tropical depression with maximum sustained winds of about 35 mph. It said the storm was centered near latitude 13.8 north, longitude 94.3 west, or about 180 miles south-southeast of <LOCATION> Salina </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. It said the storm was moving west at about 9 mph. Public Safety Minister <PERSON> Reynaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Tefel </PERSON>, head of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s national emergency committee, told diplomats in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> that the hurricane death toll had risen by 10, to 60, in a country already battered by seven years of civil war. Officials worked to restore power and water in the capital. Public buses and trucks were pressed into service to take evacuees home. No public transport was operating between <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and the rest of the country. Nationwide, only about 40 percent of public transport was running. The official <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nicaragua </ORGANIZATION> radio broadcast pleas for money and goods for the 38,000 residents of storm-wrecked <LOCATION> Bluefields </LOCATION> and other hard-hit <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> areas such as nearby <LOCATION> Corn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. `` Paradise in Ruins,'' the official <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <PERSON> Barricada </PERSON> said in a headline over the first photographs from the island. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said it was giving $ 17,000 to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s national emergency committee. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> donated $ 140,000 and offered $ 500,000 worth of technical assistance. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> offered $ 100,000 to help the homeless. The French medical group, Doctors Without Borders, said a 16-member medical team and 17 tons of supplies would arrive in <LOCATION> Bluefields </LOCATION> on Wednesday. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and private humanitarian groups in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> promised to send medical personnel and supplies. Relief supplies from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> were already being distributed. The White House said Monday it did n't expect a request for help. When specifically asked, however, President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> said this country would accept <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hurricane aid if it were offered without conditions. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> previously said the best aid the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could offer would be to stop supporting the rebels, known as Contras. The government estimates its 7-year-old war with the Contras has caused damage worth $ 12 billion. In <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said the discovery of two drowning victims near the border with <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> pushed the storm death toll there to 23. He reckoned damage at $ 62 million and said the hurricane flooded 75 towns, destroyed 1,500 homes, damaged six hospitals and ruined banana, coffee, rice and bean crops. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> told a news conference that <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, a nation of 2.5 million people, would need international help to recover. `` Places like <LOCATION> Neilly </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cortes </PERSON>, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeledon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Palmar </PERSON> <PERSON> Norte </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dominical </PERSON> and Parrita are cut off,'' he reported. In <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, states of alert were canceled as <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> moved away. No damage or injuries were reported in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and a two-week cycling tour resumed Tuesday in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> after being cut short by 10 miles Monday because of rain.
