<HEAD>Soviet Party Admits Sober-Up Campaign Has Faults</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> admitted Tuesday that its 3-year-old anti-alcoholism campaign has created long lines at liquor stores and led to a moonshining business that has left sugar and candy in short supply. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official news agency, said the party's policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> adopted a resolution reviewing President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s drive to sober up this nation of 284 million people. None of the Soviet media said when the resolution was approved. According to <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the resolution said the campaign has reduced drinking on the job and in public places, improved family life and cut alcohol-related crime. But it added that `` radical changes have not yet been achieved.'' Sugar and candy shortages developed as moonshiners hoarded sugar to make what they call in Russian `` samogon.'' The anti-alcoholism campaign has caused nationwide disgruntlement and rationing of sugar in many areas. Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> said the `` rush to curtail sales'' of alcohol led to profiteering, poisonings and drug addiction. The Soviet press has been full of reports of these problems but the resolution was one of the frankest official admissions of the program's faults. While saying drunkenness must still be fought vigorously, the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> ordered ministries to `` stamp out alcoholic queues,'' according to <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION>. Lines stretching for blocks are common at liquor stores and other shops where alcohol is sold throughout the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The reports did not say how the long lines would be eliminated but said alcohol sales would not be permitted near schools, factories, recreation areas or on public transport. The Trud labor daily said on Oct. 6 that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> plans next year to produce more beer, wine, cognac and champagne to meet popular demand. It said vodka and other strong drinks would continue to be manufactured in limited quantities. In May 1985, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> ordered a cut in production of alcoholic beverages, an increase in their price, an increase in the minimum drinking age to 21 and cuts in the hours and number of stores that could sell the products.
