<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Energy Department should value its planned sale of a synthetic gas plant in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> as worth $ 200 million instead of the $ 600 million figure it has advertised, according to congressional auditors. Even so, the sale of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> coal gasification plant near <LOCATION> Beulah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, will still yield more than the government could expect by operating it over the next 21 years, said analysts from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. In a report dated Oct. 21 and received Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> analysts said the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> should not count about $ 300 million in tax credits that the prospective buyer, <ORGANIZATION> Basin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION>, has agreed to forgo. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the department had not seen the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report but as a general matter believes it is legitimate to count the value of the tax credits that will not be used. `` That's cash the government would not have had; that's quite legitimate,'' <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> said. Using figures to calculate the loss of future income from the sale of the plant's gas at prices forecast by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> calculated the sale as yielding the equivalent of $ 203 million to the government. That is midway between the respective $ 284 million and $ 128 million figures that two consultants, <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Econometrics </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, calculated using their forecasts of future energy prices. The value to the government of the future revenues under government ownership would be $ 166 million using department projections, $ 230 million using Data Resources' estimates and a loss of $ 54 million using <PERSON> Wharton </PERSON>'s estimates, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The plant cost $ 2.1 billion to build and was a technical success at turning lignite into pipeline-quality gas. Its builders, though, defaulted on $ 1.5 billion in government guaranteed loans, leaving the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to pay off the loans and take over the plant.
