<HEAD>First Lady Wants No Exceptions to Punishment for Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY26</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wall Street bankers who buy `` cocaine on their lunch break'' should be punished along with drug dealers, smugglers and Colombian narcotics barons, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Tuesday. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> first lady told a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> committee on social affairs the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is responsible for its own drug problem and every American drug user `` is an accomplice to every criminal act, every murder, every terrorist attack carried out by the narcotics syndicates.'' `` To get serious about stopping illegal drugs ... that means confronting all those citizens who use drugs,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, and if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can not conquer the demand for narcotics there is little hope of halting production and smuggling. Her advice to all drug users, from poor children to affluent adults both here and abroad, was `` Just Say ` No','' the slogan of the anti-drug program she sponsors. `` It is often easier to make strong speeches about foreign drug lords or drug smugglers than to arrest a pair of Wall Street investment bankers buying cocaine on their lunch break,'' she said in her address to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Third Committee on Social and Humanitarian Affairs. During his eight years in office, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has advocated a war on drug producers in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and elsewhere, along with interdiction of drugs being smuggled into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. His wife said Tuesday stopping drug use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is as important as halting the production and smuggling of illegal narcotics. `` While most of the illegal drugs are imported, the drug users are home-grown,'' she said. `` If we lack the will to fully mobilize the forces of law in our own country to arrest and punish drug users, if we can not stem the American demand for drugs, then there will be little hope of preventing foreign drug producers from fulfilling that demand. `` Drugs must remain illegal at every step in the chain.''
