<HEAD>Army Says Nine Police, Four Election Officials Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leftist guerrillas dynamited a bus carrying police and election officials in the remote Andes mountains of northwest <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> Tuesday, killing 13 people and wounding 14, officials reported. The casualties brought to 51 the number of people killed in guerrilla attacks since Sunday night. An added blow to the government was the collapse of negotiations aimed at averting a one-day general strike set for Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bolivar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, an umbrella group for all six leftist rebel factions in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, urged President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> to start peace talks with the guerrillas. <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaviria </PERSON>, minister of government, issued a statement Tuesday said the proposal was made in a message sent to the president a day earlier. Guerrillas, who support the strike call, blew up the bus Tuesday morning near <LOCATION> Peque </LOCATION>, a town of 7,000 people about 200 miles northwest of the capital of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. The guerrillas set off dynamite in the road as the bus was going by, the army's 4th Brigade said in a communique from its headquarters in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>. An election for mayor was held last Sunday in <LOCATION> Peque </LOCATION>. The police had been guarding the town against guerrilla attack and the election officials had supervised voting there. Results of the election were not yet known. The military communique said nine policemen and four civilian election officials were killed and 12 policemen and two election officials wounded in the dynamating. Talks broke off Monday between labor unions and government officials. Little hope was seen of avoiding the general strike, <PERSON> Gaviria </PERSON> said in the statement. The unions want pay increases, a price freeze and an end to death squad attacks that have killed 180 union members in the last two years. The unions are the Workers' Unitary Central, the General Confederation of Labor and the Colombian Confederation of Workers. The unions, with about 800,000 members, represent about 10 percent of the work force in this nation of 30 million people. All schools and many businesses and transport companies close during general strikes in fear of violence. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said last week it discovered guerrilla plans to provoke violence during the strike. Guerrillas in a speeding car threw a bomb Tuesday at the offices of a bus company in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>, but no one was hurt, a national police communique said.
