<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY97</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, the 6-year-old whose death last year elicited an outpouring of grief and rage, was a murder victim, brutally battered by the only father she ever knew, a prosecutor charged Tuesday. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> `` beat <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> so severely that he inflicted those injures which caused her death,'' said Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Casolaro </PERSON> in a 30-minute statement at the start of <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s murder trial `` We expect to show by the evidence that he killed that child,'' <PERSON> Casolaro </PERSON> told the panel `` graphic and grotesque'' evidence and testimony will prove <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> murdered <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>, who was found unconscious in the <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> apartment early Nov. 2, 1987, and died of her injuries three days later. The prosecutor told the jury the first-grader had bruises on her chest, legs, arms and neck, along with head injuries caused by `` blunt-force trauma,'' when she arrived at the hospital that morning. Police officers there noticed <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s wounded, bleeding knuckles, he said. As <PERSON> Casolaro </PERSON> detailed the child's injuries, <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s biological mother, <PERSON> Michele </PERSON> <PERSON> Launders </PERSON>, sat crying in the front row of the courtroom. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, 47, once a respected millionaire defense lawyer, is charged with second-degree murder in the death of the child he adopted illegally at birth from Ms. Launders, then an unmarried teen-ager. He has denied ever hitting <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s attorney, <LOCATION> Ira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, urging the jury to concentrate on the facts and not his client's morality, maintained in his 10-minute argument that the evidence in the much-anticipated trial will not support a murder charg