ing arguments, Police Officer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Botte </PERSON> _ the first person to arrive at the <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> apartment and see the unconscious girl _ testified the home was dirty, unkempt and dark when he arrived. His testimony was corroborated by the next witness, paramedic <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Filangeri </PERSON>, who added that when he asked <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> to bring a lamp into the room, the defendant replied, `` Is that really important?'' <PERSON> Filangeri </PERSON> also testified that Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> answered the front door when he arrived at the apartment, and described her battered condition. `` She appeared to be 70 to 80 years of age. She had numerous facial injuries, some old, some new,'' <PERSON> Filangeri </PERSON> recalled. `` She had gray hair and was stooped.'' <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s 16-month-old brother, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, was found in the apartment sitting in a dirty diaper and tethered to a playpen, authorities have said. The boy was also illegally adopted, and now lives with his birth mother. In <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s version of what happened the night of Nov. 1, 1987, <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> became sick after eating and the bruises on her back and chest resulted from his efforts to revive her after she fell unconscious in their home. No help was called for <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> until after 6:30 a.m. on Nov. 2, court records show. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> was pronounced brain dead on Nov. 5. The slaying of the girl drew national attention and produced a city-wide outpouring of grief for the girl and rage against <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>. The doorway of her <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> home was turned into a virtual shrine, filled with flowers, gifts and poems from people who never knew <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>. Her wake and funeral drew tremendous crowds of strangers, many of them with tears in their eyes. Grou