<HEAD>Grenada Salutes 5th Anniversary of U.S. Invasion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf pvs, Other Americans ... CORRECTING full name
and title of Melton.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISTER HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> band played `` God Bless <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' and sailors from the frigate USS <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> marched in review Tuesday as Grenadians celebrated the fifth anniversary of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion that ousted a Marxist junta. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials joined a crowd of about 1,500 for a military parade in the Queen's Park sports stadium to mark the invasion. Oct. 25 is now known as Thanksgiving Day on the island and is a national holiday. The American marchers were joined by <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>'s police force and coast guard. A police unit marched in a formation that made the number 5, for the anniversary. A message from Presdident <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> read by <PERSON> Ball </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> had made major progress since 1983, paid tribute to the 19 American servicemen killed in the invasion of the nation twice the size of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and declared: `` The <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> that we know today, a free, peaceful country, is the best confirmation that those lives were not lost in vain.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, joined by seven Eastern Caribbean nations that provided token forces, sent 6,000 Marines and paratroopers to <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> to expel a Marxist military junta that had seized power in a coup. Six days earlier, soldiers had executed Prime Minister <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> and 10 other officials of his leftist government, killed scores of bystanders with mortars and automatic weapons and placed the country under 24-hour curfew. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> was overthrown as a result of factional feuding within his government. It was the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military intervention in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> in two decades and was widely criticized abroad as a violation of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>'s sovereignty. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said the invasion was mounted at the request of the Organization of Eastern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which feared <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> would use <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> as a staging area communist aggression in the region. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> denied any aggressive aims in <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>'s 94,100 residents generally regard the invasion, which the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration called a `` rescue mission,'' as a liberation from repression and near-anarchy. In a speech Tuesday, Prime Minister <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaize </PERSON> chided Grenadians `` who were on their knees in 1983'' but had forgotten `` the deliverance that God had worked for them.'' `` It was God who sent the Americans and <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> forces to deliver them,'' <PERSON> Blaize </PERSON> said. Prime Minister <PERSON> Eugenia </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION>, one of the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> leaders supporting the invasion, said it was undertaken to restore democracy and order and to safeguard <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens on the island, but above all was necessary `` to save our own skins.'' A memorial service was held at the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Anse </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, where 480 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students were evacuated by helicopter. A bronze monument on the campus bears the names of the 19 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen who died in the operation. Forty-four Grenadians and 24 Cubans also were killed. Since the invasion, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has poured $ 110 million into <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> to finish an international airport started by <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, pave hundreds of miles of potholed roads and improve electricity, telephone and water systems. Parliamentary democracy is well-established and tourism has improved, but not to the extent expected just after the invasion. A hoped-for flood of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment has not materialized and the island's economy, based on agriculture, continues to struggle. Other Americans at the ceremony included Vice Adm. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Metcalf </PERSON>, commander of the invasion; Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>, chief of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> armed forces in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of state for the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooper </ORGANIZATION>, charge d'affaires at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>.
