<HEAD>Faulty Pilot Maneuver Blamed for Commuter Crash That Killed 12</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `The NTSB criticized,' with 3 new
grafs to EXPAND on AVAir financial problems and that it sold
commuter operations to American Airlines last May</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal investigators on Tuesday blamed a quick turn during takeoff for the crash of an AVAir commuter plane last February at <LOCATION> Raleigh-Durham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, airport. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the pilot of the aircraft maneuvered too sharply at low altitude, resulting in the loss of control and crash that killed 12 people on board. The AVAir commuter plane, flying as <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> Flight 378, crashed shortly after it departed the airport in dense fog on Feb. 19, l988, landing in a wooded area about a mile from the runway. The Fairchild Metro III commuter was bound for <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, with 10 passengers, a pilot and a co-pilot. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the probable cause for the accident was `` the failure of the flight crew to maintain a proper flight path due to the first officer's inappropriate instrument scan, the captain's inadequate monitoring of the flight and the flight crew's response to a fault in the airplane's stall avoidance system.'' The investigation revealed that the co-pilot, <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Digan </PERSON>, 28, who had been hired by AVAir in May 1987, had a spotty training record and on a number of occasions had been the subject of poor evaluations by various AVAir captains. In September 1987, another AVAir captain reported in an evaluation that Ms. <PERSON> Digan </PERSON> had problems in climb, cruise, descent and landing maneuvers. Two months before that, another captain wrote AVAir's operations director on hotel stationery that he considered Ms. <PERSON> Digan </PERSON>'s performance in landing his airplane `` unacceptable'' and that on their trip she had trouble with eight of 10 landings. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> criticized AVAir, which no longer operates commuter flights, for not acting sooner to deal with Ms. <PERSON> Digan </PERSON>'s flying problems. It also said the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to monitor adequately AVAir's financial and operational problems was a contributing factor to the Feb. 19 accident. AVAir, which since l985 had a marketing agreement with <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, underwent rapid growth in l987 after <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> expanded its hub operation at <LOCATION> Raleigh-Durham </LOCATION>. It hired 123 pilots in the second quarter of l987 alone and by l988, about 60 percent of its pilots had less than a year with the company. But AVAir began having financial problems in late l987, filed for protection under the bankruptcy laws on Jan. 15, l988 and ceased operation, only to resume flights on Feb. 3, about two weeks before the crash. Last May, AVAir sold its commuter operations to <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> which continues to fly those operations under the name <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION>. Investigators determined that Ms. <PERSON> Digan </PERSON> was at the controls when the <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> III </ORGANIZATION> commuter plane departed <LOCATION> Raleigh-Durham </LOCATION> on Feb. 19, although there was evidence that the captain, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, 38, attempted to help keep the aircraft aloft in the final seconds. Flight 378 had been told by air traffic control to bank to the right as soon as possible after takeoff because of the heavy traffic loads at the time of the departure, investigators said. But Ms. <PERSON> Digan </PERSON>, the investigation concluded, banked the aircraft too sharply and at too low an altitude _ about a 40 degree bank only 200 feet off the ground, or nearly twice as sharp as would have been advised. The plane was relying on instruments because of the heavy fog and the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> concluded that if the pilots had scanned their instruments adequately they would have known their bank was too sharp and at too low an altitude. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> report said the pilots also might have been distracted by a light indicating that the aircraft's stall warning system had activated. The system automatically forces the nose down if the aircraft is approaching a stall situation. But, according to the investigation, the aircraft's performance indicated that the stall warning system actually had not deployed, but that the problem stemmed from a false warning light.
</TEXT>
