<HEAD>Yugoslav Government Plans Meeting on Economic Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government leaders will meet in emergency session this week on <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s economic crisis, <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency announced Tuesday. It said the Cabinet and nine-member collective Presidency will meet in joint session Friday. Only two such meetings have been held since the Communists came to power after World War II _ in April 1981 and November 1985. `` The mere fact that the Presidency has decided to convene the joint session indicates the gravity of the situation facing our country's economy,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said. Premier <PERSON> Branko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> said in a recent interview that the government will introduce `` a completely new market-oriented economic system.'' The plan, which could be adopted by Parliament by the end of the year, envisages closing down all money-losing firms, the wide introduction of both <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> and foreign capital investments and the sales of stocks and bonds. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is beset by ethnic and social unrest as well as its worst economic crisis since World War II. The nation's inflation rate is running at more than 217 percent, the highest in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has a $ 21 billion foreign debt and a 15 percent unemployment rate. Labor dissatisfaction has grown worse since May, when government austerity measures chopped wagwes and allowed substantial price increases. About half of the nation's companies, employing about 2 million workers, are losing money and layoffs could trigger more social restivity. Other developments Tuesday came in the ethnic conflict involving Montenegrins, Slavs and ethnic Albanians. The Parliament of the southern republic of <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION> gave a confidence vote to all but five members of the 20-member <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> following a debate over police actions during a demonstration, accord