<HEAD>U.N. Panel Calls For Direct Peace Talks Between Morocco and
Polisario</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> decolonization committee on Tuesday called on <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and the Polisario independence movement to start direct peace talks to settle their war for sovereignty over the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>. The committee, officially known as the <ORGANIZATION> Fourth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, voted 87-0 with 53 abstentions in favor of the motion sponsored by <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, an ally of the Marxist-led Polisario movement. Polisario has been fighting for independence for the former Spanish colony since 1975, when the colonial administration left and Moroccan troops and settlers took over the sparsely populated, 110,000-square-mile territory in northwest <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> opposes direct talks with <PERSON> Polisario </PERSON>, saying that negotiating with the movement as an equal before the Saharans have chosen them as their representative would grant <PERSON> Poliario </PERSON> a status they have not earned. Most of the sponsors of Tuesday's motion were socialist and developing nations. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> voted in favor of the motion; the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and most other Western nations abstained. <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> did not vote. The motion calls on <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Polisario </LOCATION> to begin direct negotiations for a cease-fire and for holding a referendum on seld-determination for the <LOCATION> Saharan </LOCATION> people. It also welcomed the acceptance by both sides in principle of Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s proposal that they honor a truce and hold the referendum. Polisario spokesmen say that so far in indirect talks through the secretary-general, the two parties have only agreed on the wording of the referendum, which will be for either independence or affiliation with <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, and that only people counted as Saharans in the last colonial census in 1974 will be eligible to vote. That census put the population at 76,000. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> plans to send about 2,000 peacekeeping troops to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> to monitor the referendum and see that Moroccan troops and Polisario fighters remain in their barracks and camps. Polisario says it has about 7,000 fighters in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>, and that <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> has 185,000 soldiers there. The independence movement says that all except 7,000 Moroccan troops should withdraw to their homeland before the referendum is conducted.
