<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A one-time whiz kid of carpet cleaning took the witness stand in his securities fraud trial Tuesday and admitted he manipulated stocks and defrauded investors in a multimillion-dollar swindle. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, 22, assuming an embarrassed, shy demeanor, also began laying out for jurors a defense of duress in which he claims that organized crime figures dictated his every move. <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> told jurors he was threatened with broken limbs or death if he did n't run his business according to the dictates of two men _ one who he said tried to sexually molest him and the other `` a Nazi'' who defamed <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>'s Jewish heritage. `` I felt like I was taking money from the devil,'' he said of his alliance with the second man. <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> described how he came under the sway of the first man, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Krowpman </PERSON>, a 230-pound weight lifter, tool salesman and reputed loan shark who befriended <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> at a gym where he exercised in his early teens. `` He was my idol,'' said <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>. `` He was everything because he had money; he had build. He had everything I did n't have. ... He was nice to me. He was like the father I never had. I loved him.'' But he indicated <PERSON> Krowpman </PERSON> had a cruel side that surfaced when he would arrive at the gym with a 6-foot-9, 330-pound weight lifter he introduced as `` Big Steve.'' `` When him and <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> were together it was like night and day,'' said <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>. `` They would tease me about being puny and not able to lift weights. They would throw me in the pool with my clothes on. It was n't the same.'' Later, he said, <PERSON> Krowpman </PERSON> gave him $ 1,600 to set up his carpet cleaning business but began demanding payments of $ 200 a month plus 50 per cent of the profits. He also blurted out that <PERSON> Krowpman </PERSON> once tried to molest him and said he began paying him `` after the attempted rape.'' <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>'s lawyer has said <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, who launched his <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> carpet cleaning company at 16 in his parents garage, was beaten and threatened by mobsters who used him to perpetuate a $ 25 million stock fraud. But prosecutors have portrayed <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> as a shrewd con man who bilked investors for his own benefit, selling them on the future of a business that for the most part did not exist. <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> is charged with 57 counts of securities fraud, credit card fraud and mail fraud. Ten of his 12 co-defendants, including <PERSON> Krowpman </PERSON>, have pleaded guilty to various charges related to the ZZZZ Best operation. Accountant <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothberg </PERSON> is on trial with <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, accused of taking a bribe to cover up ZZZZ Best's frauds. The husky, dark-haired <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> appeared nervous in his initial moments on the stand. As his lawyer, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenner </PERSON>, asked him to admit he had done the acts charged in the indictment, there were long pauses and he bowed his head as if ashamed before he answered. Asked if he had made false claims for his business, <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> replied softly: `` It's true. I made those claims and they were all lies.'' The case is being heard by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Dickran </PERSON> <PERSON> Tavrizian </PERSON>.
