<FIRST>r a AM-Drought-Economy     10-25 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought-Economy,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economist: Drought Not The Disaster Some Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The drought of 1988 was not the economic disaster some expected and might turn out to be a bonanza for some farmers, an agricultural economist said Tuesday. `` The drought likely will have minimal impact on overall farm financial conditions,'' said <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Some people _ and I would cite those who came into 1988 with crops from previous years, and the large number of farmers who had normal or near-normal yields _ they're having one of their best years in 10.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said there's no question that some farms were hurt, or that most farmers saw decreases in yields. Livestock producers in particular will suffer because feed prices are increasing in a period when selling prices are down. But about 60 percent of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s agricultural operations are crop-related, and while yields are down they are for the most part more than offset by crop price increases, he said. `` Your yields may be down 25 percent, but prices are up 30 percent or more,'' he said. `` From that perspective, while there may be a few isolated cases of the drought pushing an already stressed operation over the edge, for the most part, it'll have a neutral effect on farm financial issues. `` We'll even see ... another small rise in farm land prices,'' he said. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Durliat </PERSON>, communications director for the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said the situation was improving, but he disagreed that some farmers are having banner years Drought-related losses `` are not going to be as widespread as originally feared,'' <PERSON> Durliat </PERSON> said. `` But you'll still hear about a lot of farmers who were put behind the eight-ball by this drought.'' Rep. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Oxley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s assessment was generally correct. <PERSON> Oxley </PERSON> said 7 inches of rain in his district in August `` brought the corn crop back when they had given it up for dead.'' The federal government in July declared <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and several other states disaster areas, making low-interest loans available to farmers and freeing government stores of feed and federal set-aside acreage for livestock producers.
