<FIRST>r w AM-Pensions     10-25 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pensions,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moratorium Imposed on Pension Plan Reversions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has imposed a six-month moratorium on allowing companies to capture excess assets through termination of their overfunded pension plans. The department said it directed the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> on Monday to delay until May 1 next year approval of pension plan terminations in which excess assets would be recovered by employer sponsors of the plans. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, corporate sponsors of defined benefit pension plans have recovered a total of $ 18.8 billion since 1980 by terminating 1,752 overfunded plans and funding their liabilities through annuities or newly established plans. In the first half of 1988, 30 companies terminated overfunded pension plans, recapturing $ 199 million in excess assets, said the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION>, a government agency that insures defined benefit pension plan participants against losses much like the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crop </ORGANIZATION>. insures bank depositors. `` This moratorium will give <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> time to come up with legislation that will make certain that workers and retirees get a fair share of those funds,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> sponsored legislation in the last <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to heavily tax any surplus pension plan assets that revert to companies through terminations as a way to discourage the practice. The measure was stricken from the tax bill that was passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last week in exchange for an agreement by the administration to impose the moratorium. Under the current law, such reversions are allowed as long as vested participants in the plans are assured the pensions accrued to them at the time of termination. Unions and advocacy groups for the elderly and pensioners have maintained that companies should be prevented from capturing excess assets from the plans in order to insure against possible future investment losses and provide cost-of-living increases to pensioners. Business groups, whose members have used surplus pension plan assets in the past several years as a source of capital, have opposed major changes in the law. `` There is a longstanding precedent that these assets belong to the employer,'' <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilroy </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> lobbyist, said Tuesday. `` The whole issue boils down to the one question of whose assets are these.'' Since employers have to make up the difference when a pension plan runs short, they ought to be able to tap the surplus when a pension plan's investments produce higher-than-expected dividends, he said. However, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, a lobbyist for the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said the surpluses enable companies to say `` yes'' when retirees ask for cost-of-living increases. `` They're funded to be on-going,'' she said. `` The companies get tax breaks because they're on-going.''
</TEXT>
