<HEAD>Anne Frank Letters Sold At Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two letters and a postcard written by <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> and her sister, <PERSON> Margot </PERSON>, were sold to an anonymous bidder at an auction Tuesday for $ 150,000. The young Jewish Holocaust victims mailed the notes along with two photographs to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> pen pals in 1940, a month before <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> invaded the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, prompting the <PERSON> Franks </PERSON> to go into hiding. The successful bidder said he represented `` a number of institutions'' but would not specify further, said <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Swann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Galleries </ORGANIZATION>, the auction house. However, the bidder did say he would announce on Wednesday the name of the institution where the letters will be kept, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. Also on the auction block were pages from <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Edison </PERSON>'s notebooks, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>'s certificate of conversion to <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION>, and a collection of <PERSON> Greta </PERSON> <PERSON> Garbo </PERSON> correspondence Bidding for the Frank collection was over in five minutes. <PERSON> Swann </PERSON> had predicted bidding would exceed $ 30,000 but could not estimate how high it would go because nothing written by <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> had ever been auctioned. Among the bidders for the letters was actress <PERSON> Whoopi </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, one of hundreds who participated in the auction by telephone. About 250 people attended the sale in person. The correspondence between the two sisters and their pen pals in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> was dated April 27 and April 29, 1940. It described the girls' life at home and school in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> <PERSON> Margot </PERSON> wrote that `` having a frontier with <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and being a small country we never feel safe.'' A month after the letters were sent, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> invaded the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Franks </PERSON> went into hiding but were later discovered and sent to concentration camps. <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>'s diary, published in 1952, carries a poignant account of their life in hiding. The <PERSON> Franks </PERSON>' pen-pals were sisters from <LOCATION> Danville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Juanita </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, 11, who was <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>'s age, and <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, 15, who was <PERSON> Margot </PERSON>'s age. The <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> sisters wrote back, but never heard from the <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> girls again. After the war, they wrote again, and <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>'s father replied, explaining that he was the only one in his family to survive the war. The Wagner sisters, now living in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, decided earlier this year to sell the letters. `` We had been discussing what I was going to do to retire. I've never really saved very much,'' said <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, who was reached by telephone at her home in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area. Miss <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> also said she plans to donate part of the money from the sale to <ORGANIZATION> Wayfarer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit organization she founded nine years ago to ship books to missionaries. She and her sister hope to travel to <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> to visit the house where <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> hid with her family, <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> said. `` We'd worried about her during the war but never dreamed that she was suffering.'' Also sold at the auction were several <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> autographs, including her certificate of conversion to <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION>, which took place just prior to her marriage to playwright <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. The certificate was bought by a private collector for $ 7,000, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. A handwritten letter of condolence from <PERSON> Emily </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> to the husband of a friend who died brought $ 8,000 from a dealer, he said. Seventy-six pages of handwritten notes by <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Edison </PERSON> brought $ 32,000. <PERSON> Edison </PERSON> compiled the manuscript, which concerns his travels, jobs and inventions, for use by his official biographers, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. A collection of correspondence from <PERSON> Greta </PERSON> <PERSON> Garbo </PERSON> was bought by a collector for $ 9,500, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said.
