<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs Oct. 28, or thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Male Domination Called Result Of Sin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Religious feminists fume at that old passage in Genesis 3:16 about women, `` Your desire shall be for your husband, and he shall rule over you.'' However, no less a religious authority than Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> says the passage refers to a flawed condition in humanity and it is not supposed to be that way. `` This ` domination' indicates the disturbance and the loss of the stability of that fundamental equality which the man and woman possess in the ` unity of the two,''' he says. It results from original sin, he says, from the human attempt to be supreme and outrival God. `` The overcoming of this evil inheritance is, generation after generation, the task of every human being, whether man or women,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> says. Although his recent letter on women plainly kept them barred from his church's priesthood, it still hacked away at some of the old religious biases against them. In fact, he describes woman as the `` biblical exemplar'' from the beginning of history to its close. He notes that at the end of time, she is portrayed in Revelation 12:1 as `` a woman clothed with the sun, with the moon under her feet, and on her head a crown of stars.'' `` One can say she is a woman of cosmic scale, on a scale with the whole of creation,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> says of the symbolism, marveling at woman's high role. `` God entrusts the human being to her in a special way.'' The pope says the exceptional womanly prerogative also shows up in a woman being the means by which divinity joined humanity in Christ `` born to a woman,'' <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nazareth </LOCATION>. `` Thus there begins the central event, the key event in the history of salvation,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> says. `` A woman is to be found at the center of this salvific event.'' Although the pope's Sept. 30 teaching letter, `` Mulieris Dignitatem'' -LRB- The Dignity of Women -RRB- drew scant attention and only mixed reactions, it offers some rare papal rebukes to common religious slights against women. He even tackles the pervasive masculine images of God _ a regular and controversial target of Christian feminists _ declaring that God's creativity is `` neither `` ` masculine' nor ` feminine','' but `` totally divine.'' While humanity is created in `` likeness'' to God, there also is a `` non-likeness'' to him, the `` Different One'' or `` totally Other,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> says. He adds that the Bible's characteristic anthropomorphic way of speaking about God refers to his `` fatherhood,'' but that does n't mean maleness as in human fatherhood He points out that various Scripture passages attribute to God both masculine and feminine qualities, sometimes picturing him as a caring, comforting mother. `` Thus every element of human generation which is proper to man, and every element which is proper to woman, namely human ` fatherhood' and ` motherhood,' bear within itself a likeness to, or analogy with the divine ` generating' which is in God,'' the pope says. He says that women possess `` essential equality'' with men, that both `` are human beings to an equal degree, both are created in God's image.'' While the biblical narrative says that sin was initiated by the woman, Eve, followed by man, <PERSON> Adam </PERSON>, the pope rejects that twist putting the prior blame on women, declaring: `` There is no doubt that, independent of this ` distinction of roles,' that first sin is the sin of man, created by <PERSON> God </PERSON> as male and female. It is also the sin of the ` first parents' ... `` As the author of the evil of sin, the human being _ man and woman _ is affected by it.'' Besides emphasizing the role of a woman, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>, as the channel by which God entered humanity in <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>, the pope pictures women as key figures in his ministry, and him as a sort of the original women's liberator <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> `` became a promoter of women's true dignity and of the vocation corresponding to this dignity,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> says. `` At times this caused wonder and surprise, often to the point of scandal.'' Furthermore, the pope notes, women played major roles in his ministry: Women supported it with their means. The Samaritan woman became his first mass evangelist. Women stood by him at the cross while male apostles hid in fear. In `` this most arduous test of faith and fidelity the women proved stronger than the apostles,'' the pope observes. Women also were the first to report the empty tomb after the resurrection and the first to meet the risen Christ and proclaim it to others. Women take an unusual precedence, as the pope describes it, but he still sees the priesthood as limited to males.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Oct. 28.</NOTE>
