<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv26   10-25 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 26,0783</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday Oct. 26</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Letter to Tovarich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Capitalism is an ingenious creator, a constant revolution in which new destroys old, a riotous, unruly process that proceeds with no respect for central planning. Those observations come from an open letter to <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> citizens, now beginning to experiment with capitalism, from an American corporate economist. It concludes with the assurance that `` you have our sympathy in full measure.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffen </PERSON>, vice president and corporate economist for <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION>, wrote the letter to a mythical tovarich, or comrade, as a means of making some points about capitalism that escape even Americans. Soviet leaders are misinformed, says <PERSON> Griffen </PERSON>, if they believe the party can control capitalism to meet party needs. If Soviet leaders are able to graft private enterprise onto Russian rootstock, `` they will have no hope of controlling its growth to conform to a previously established acceptable norm,'' says <PERSON> Griffen </PERSON>. `` If you import real capitalism, tovarich, be prepared for riotous unruly growth that pays little heed and no respect to plot plans,'' he writes in a company publication, `` AEconomics,'' reminding Russians that capitalism builds but also destroys. He cites <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumpeter </PERSON>, one of the greatest of Western economists, who expressed respect for capitalism's power to build, but observed also that it has an enormous power to tear down what it had previously built. `` Count on it, tovarich, capitalism can tear down what you have built, too, and surely will do so if given half a chance. Our bombers and our missiles can not so thoroughly change your landscape as capitalism can.'' He explains: `` Who can say what capitalism will create in your country to take the place of what it destroys. `` The enterprise system within which we live provides incentives to people to follow their dreams, to create the life they wish to live and to learn how to support it. `` When millions of people are free to behave in this manner, ingeniouus solutions to problems appear as if by magic. Amazing efficiencies are discovered. Human needs and wants are fulfilled better, faster and less expensively _ capitalism has survived because it serves people better than any other social arrangement.'' But, again, it has little respect for tradition. As capitalism reinvents itself it tramples on old products, businesses, jobs, ways of doing business, ways of living, he says. It is a process of creative destruction. It precedes a long wave or surge of progress. It happened in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> during the Great Depression of the 1930s, says <PERSON> Griffen </PERSON>. The people of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, who enjoy one of the world's highest standards of living, even now complain about the loss of the old ways In <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, he says, you may find many examples of misguided capitalism and little of its creativity. Birthing pangs are felt in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ in whatever nations `` rotate through the headlines.'' They are felt in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and always will be so long as the process of revolutionary renewal continues. The automotive industry, for instance, had been in a depression as a result of new ways of making cars with new materials by different people in distant countries. `` Jobs have been lost in automobile companies and in the unions and suppliers that deal with them. Local communities have been affected. Old factories have become new shopping malls or condominiums.'' The same is true in agriculture and finance, says <PERSON> Griffen </PERSON>, observing that `` recently it has reached an intensity as to have touched nearly everyone's life.'' He observes that the power of the market has thrown hundreds of thousands out of work, but it has also created millions of jobs. Statistically, he says, this is an enormous net gain, `` but for those whose old way of life was disrupted there has been a real cost not measured in gross national product.'' Will it work in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>? <PERSON> Griffen </PERSON> writes tovarich: `` Your leaders hope the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> can maintain control of this revolution, but that seems unlikely. Russian capitalism will create power centers, interest groups and spheres of influence too numerous to count let alone control.'' The capitalist way of life, he reminds his mythical comrade, is a diametric opposite to totalitarian or authoritarian central control. `` Ask anyone in the West: Capitalism produces the constantly revolutionary society.'' Only temporarily, he says, are central control and capitalism reconcilable. `` Your leaders are now yielding to the realization of which is the greater force.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday Oct 26</NOTE>
