<HEAD>Church Council Threatened By Financial Crunch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hard financial times have hit the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, and officers say it's going to have to change its ways to keep going. `` I do n't think it's going to fold,'' said <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Sohl </PERSON>, who chairs the finance committee of the country's largest ecumenical organization. `` But it ca n't keep doing the same as it's doing now. It has to change what it's doing to bring it in line with what it can afford.'' Measures to deal with the financial crisis were to be considered at meetings of a special coordinating group this weekend and of the council's governing board Nov. 1-4 in <LOCATION> Tarrytown </LOCATION>, N.Y. The 260 board members represent the 32 denominations making up the council, including most major <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> and Eastern Orthodox bodies. They total about 40 million members. While the budgetary squeeze is described as severe and threatening, an oft-repeated view is that the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, even if dismantled, would have to be immediately recreated. `` There is too much work that the churches need to do together,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Sohl </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Several factors brought on the crunch, notably either stagnant or reduced denominational allocations to the council, which historically have lagged behind inflation and rising costs. Also, because monies received are needed at once instead of going temporarily into an investment fund, interest dropped sharply. Beyond that, controversy over increased levies on <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the council's big relief agency, to support council general services has caused some denominations to quit channeling relief funds through CWS. The council `` is shooting itself in the foot,'' said <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Rumer </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>, which has halted routing of relief money through CWS for the time being. CWS, with relief operations around the world, is by far the council's largest operation, taking up about 70 percent of a $ 52.9 million net budget. The Rev. <PERSON> Arie </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON>, the council's general secretary and chief administrator, says part of the trouble seems to be disenchantment within some mainline denominations that are mainstays of the council. Several of them, such as the Presbyterian Church -LRB- USA -RRB-, the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> have all suffered membership losses in recent years. Since its founding in 1950, the council has been a regular target of conservative groups, which have criticized it for stands on social issues, but such attacks have waned and were not considered crucial to the financial difficulties. However, with denominational concerns turning inward, taking precedence over ecumenical activities, the council has been been forced steadily to cut staff and program, most sharply in recent years. The current professional staff of 83 is expected to be cut to 61 for 1989. Previously, that staff total had dropped from 187 in 1968 to 105 in 1975. The council's associated mission medical office, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> unit that provides medical evaluations of missionaries before and after overseas service, is to cease operations Dec. 31. But plans were under way to create a new medical office in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> in conjunction with <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, which would assume the medical reviews of missionaries. Other new cutbacks include eliminating CWS' family life and population program, closing the council development office and merging its national and international disaster-response offices.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Oct. 28</NOTE>
