<HEAD>Seniority System, Hectic Hours Rankle Freshmen Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No job is perfect, not even being a member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. But once you're there, it's a difficult job to give up. No member of the freshman class of 1986 plans to leave voluntarily. Freshmen congressmen cite the slow-moving seniority system, the unpredictable floor schedule and canceled airplane reservations and speaking engagements as some of the headaches that go with the job. But along with that is the satisfaction of being a party to major pieces of legislation. Here are some impressions from five freshmen:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Guys who control the place have been here 25, 30, 35, 40 years and for a young guy coming in, boy, that's a long time,'' said Rep. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hastert </PERSON>, R-Ill. <PERSON> Hastert </PERSON>, 46, served in the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> where he became minority spokesman on the House Appropriations Committee The husky, affable former teacher and restaurateur likes <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> but at times recalls a bit wistfully the statehouse clout he surrendered to get here. `` I could pick up a phone and have the director of children and family services, public health or public aid in my office in five minutes if I needed help or to work with a problem,'' he reminisced. These days, `` I pick up the phone and go through the hierarchy,'' <PERSON> Hastert </PERSON> says. `` It's just a bigger place. You ca n't be in everybody's office in five minutes. I realize that.'' Still, he finds himself troubled by `` the time people bide here before they have a big impact on their committees.'' To <PERSON> Hastert </PERSON>, the highlight of his first two years in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was the budget summit at which lawmakers agreed on a formula to curb spending. But he says cutting the deficit remains a major challenge. `` Otherwise, I think we're headed for a fiscal train wreck.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 It's true that Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>, D-Md., has an easier time getting home than Midwestern lawmakers who must scramble to keep airplane reservations when floor sessions meander unexpectedly into the night But <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>, a former professional basketball player, said representing a district just 30 minutes from the Capitol does n't ease the hectic pace `` The proximity of my district to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> doubles it,'' he said, as he is often expected to be in two places at once. `` You plan lots of things in your district assuming that you'll be out of session at reasonable hours or that you wo n't be in session on a certain day And then all of a sudden that changes and there are very difficult things to cancel.'' Sending an aide to apologize to impatient constituents is a risky move for a lawmaker who won his seat by just 428 votes. To make the strain even worse, <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> had vowed to compile a 100 percent attendance record on votes _ a rarity even among the most conscientious congressmen. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> sometimes takes meaningless procedural votes, such as approving the previous day's journal, and lawmakers secure about re-election sometimes pass up such time-consuming formalities <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> achieved that 100 percent record this term but says it ca n't last forever. The one-time <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> scholar began his term by being elected president of the Democratic freshman class. `` There are n't many jobs in the world where you can work on issues of such great diversity,'' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> said. But he finds himself chafing at times by the slowness with which Capitol Hill changes its longstanding traditions. `` I think they could move this institution more toward the 20th century,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Grandy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, was best known as The Love Boat's <PERSON> Gopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> when he asked <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> voters to send him to the House He assured them, though, that `` there's a long-pants version of <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Grandy </PERSON>.'' Two years later, the Harvard-educated former actor said he has been `` pleasantly surprised because there's an old rubric that says a freshman's main goal is to get re-elected and you should be seen and not heard and there's very little you can accomplish.'' Not true, the 40-year-old former <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> aide said after two years on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` I've worked on every major piece of legislation that has come out of the ag committee, including working on three major conferences, drought, credit and trade bill,'' he says. Not that any freshman was a prime mover in fashioning those bills. But seniority-heavy lawmakers once known as the `` Old Bulls'' of <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> are more willing to let newcomers participate, said <PERSON> Grandy </PERSON>. `` I just hope that I'm always a Young Turk and never become an <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bull </LOCATION>,'' he added. And the hours? `` For anybody who lives west of, I think <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, this is a killer schedule.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelosi </PERSON>, D-Calif., came to <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> early in 1987 to fill a vacancy The daughter of a one-time <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> congressman and long on the fringes of national politics, the newest freshman found no surprises. `` Surprise is a word that for politicians and people in public life is a very rare occurrence,'' said <PERSON> Pelosi </PERSON>, whose district encompasses all but a sliver of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` You hope for the best, you prepare for the worst and you are very rarely surprised.'' What would she change? A long pause. `` Actually,'' she said. `` I have a lot of respect for this institution. `` It's true, it would be easier if we had more certainty about the schedule, but it's in the nature of the place and I like the fast pace and I can cope with it,'' she said. `` There are all kinds of ways to get a job done.'' High on her agenda was federal assistance for AIDS victims. She applauds congressional approval of such a bill. `` I feel very pleased about that because of what it will mean for people infected with the AIDS virus,'' she said. `` And there is plenty more to do.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunning </PERSON>, R-Ky., won 224 games as a major league pitcher, including a pair of no hitters He came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> from the <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Any surprises? `` It's only the numbers,'' <PERSON> Bunning </PERSON> said. `` You have to add three zeros to everything.'' He did find himself a bit disappointed in `` the lack of input.'' `` I think the committee chairman and the ranking member seem to have more control than they ought to,'' <PERSON> Bunning </PERSON> said. `` That is, not much legislation is altered at the full committee level and particularly in Banking.'' In the <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, he said, `` there was n't much you could do, even if you tried your darndest and I tried in certain instances.'' Would he change anything? <PERSON> Bunning </PERSON> cited proxy voting in committees _ a practice under which senior lawmakers collect the `` proxies'' of absent members and vote them on bills and amendments. Without proxy voting, he said, `` you would have to show up and vote ... and the committee chairman could not vote 15 proxies who were absent and just work his will on everything.'' He said it was hard to put his finger on any single high point over the last two years. `` I'm a well-trained professional who does n't get too high or too low,'' he said. `` That comes from my athletic background, I believe, where some you win, some you lose and some get rained out.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Oct. 28</NOTE>
