<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Haid </PERSON>'s longtime hobby of doing accents came in handy when he was cast as an Australian soldier in the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> miniseries `` The Great Escape: Return With a Vengeance.'' He plays Sgt. <PERSON> Mac </PERSON> <PERSON> MacKenzie </PERSON> in the four-hour, two-part series that is a sequel to the blockbuster 1963 movie about the true story of a huge escape of Allied airmen from a German prisoner-of-war camp in World War II. `` He's a combination of a couple of guys,'' said <PERSON> Haid </PERSON>. `` Mostly a Scot, who's still alive but was conveniently changed to an Aussie for television. My character was a tunnel digger. Moles, they called them. `` We filmed in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> with a lot of British actors. My biggest challenge was fitting in with their dialects. My hobby is doing accents. I've been fascinated by accents since I was a kid. I have a kind of parrot ear. Mostly what I did was listen to tapes. Then all of a sudden,'' slipping into an Australian accent, `` you're talkin' like that. `` The Great Escape'' sequel will be broadcast by <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday and Monday, Nov. 6-7. Besides <PERSON> Haid </PERSON>, who starred as Officer <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Renko </PERSON> for seven years on `` Hill Street Blues,'' the movie also features Christopher Reeved Fields to about 29.6 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement saying it was considering its position in the light of the British government's decision. Trade Secretary Lord <PERSON> Young </PERSON> asked the monopolies commission to report to him within the three months. The British investigation will center on the proposed takeover's impact on strategic metals, in particular titanium and zircon, a spokesman at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> said Titanium, a metal largely used as a whitener in paints, also is used in jet engines, a Consolidated Gold Fields metallurgist said. <PERSON> Zircon </PERSON> is mainly used as a refracting agent in glass and steel furnaces, but is also a critical substance in nuclear submarines and power plants, and in rocket nose cones, he said. Consolidated Gold Fields says that Australian-based <ORGANIZATION> Renison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Goldfields </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, in which it has a 49 percent stake, is the world's largest producer of mineral sands that serve as raw materials for titanium and zircon. Consolidated Gold Fields' shares plummeted on news of the investigation, while <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>'s shares rose.
