 Locked-out union workers go to the polls Friday to decide whether to accept a compromise offer aimed at breaking their 1 -LCB- - year-old labor dispute with <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION> The offer covers a six-year period retroactive to Feb. 1, 1987. The previous contract expired in January 1987 and union workers were locked out of the plant on March 21, 1987. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Langham </PERSON>, regional vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paperworkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said the proposed contract `` provides tremendous shift differential improvement and it provides that all union members would be returned to work immediately.'' One of the major issues in the labor dispute has been IP's policy of paying production employees extra when they work Sundays and holidays The company wanted to eliminate the bonuses to cut costs. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Bragg </PERSON>, president of UPIU Local 265 and a member of the committee that has represented the 1,200 locked-out workers at the bargaining table, said the company would not address the bonus issue. <PERSON> Bragg </PERSON> said the union membership appears to be `` split at this point as to who wants to fight and who wants to quit.'' `` We commend our people for fighting the battle as long as they have,'' he said. `` But at some point in time, we had to go back to the members for direction on which way they want us to go.'' Company officials have said the locked-out workers can not return to their jobs until they accept a new labor agreement. The Mobile mill has been operated by temporary workers since the start of the lockout, which spread to strikes at IP mills in three other states. Those strikes have all been called off.
