<HEAD>London Stocks Narrowly Mixed In Nervous Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices were narrowly mixed in light, nervous trading Tuesday. With few major incentives for trading, players largely were hanging back awaiting Thursday's release of British trade figures for September. `` There is a lot of nervousness over the pound, interest rates and the trade figures,'' said one dealer about the day's light level of trading activity. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was unchanged at 1,848.4 at midday. Volume was thin, with just 214.9 million shares changing hands, compared with 289.5 million shares at the same time Monday. The major market-affecting news was a keenly awaited decision by the British government to refer <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION>'s 2.9 billion-pound, or $ 5.06 billion, bid for <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Monopolies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mergers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to investigate its possible impact on competition. The decision blocked the bid from proceeding and <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION>' shares plummeted on the news, which also depressed the overall market. <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION> shares fell 104 pence to 11.41 pounds.
