<NOTE>For Release Monday Oct. 31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Asian Money Looking For Property In Atlanta</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB1 of Oct. 24</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Scarlett </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON>'s hometown is for sale, and cash-rich Japanese investors are the principal targets of businessmen marketing <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s highest profile office buildings. It is a poorly kept secret that a Japanese insurance company is about to buy the <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>, paying $ 300 million for <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s year-old showpiece skyscraper And market professionals say other buildings, principally the headquarters tower of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, hub for <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s broadcasting conglomerate, are on the block and may soon be sold to syndicates made up largely of foreign investors. The Asian invasion of the American real estate market has raised hackles elsewhere in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as major landmarks like the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> building in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> have been snapped up by the Japanese. But here in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, the phenomenon follows years of active campaigning for foreign investment. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> has been mining <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for business since the mid-70s and the state now ranks second to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in Japanese manufacturing investment. <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> ranks third among American cities behind <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> in the number of Asian-owned businesses per 1,000 Asian residents. `` Jobs. Jobs is the purpose of our efforts,'' said <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardoza </PERSON>, deputy commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> and Trade. A decade of self-promotion and airport improvements by the city and state have helped fuel the drive for foreign investment, said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Judd </PERSON>, a business consultant who was one of the founders eight years ago of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan-America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. A survey on <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> real estate by the <ORGANIZATION> Braemar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> says 12.06 percent of the city's office space is foreign-owned, and <ORGANIZATION> Braemar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> owner and managing partner <PERSON> Tarby </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> predicts 50 percent of the best office space will be foreign-owned by the year 2000, with the Japanese accounting for half `` With all of the major Japanese banks currently in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and two airlines, <ORGANIZATION> JAL </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Air Lines -RRB-, now flying direct links to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, I am confident that we will see more Japanese investors looking at our office buildings, hotels and regional malls for acquisition,'' he said. <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> `` is at the top of the second tier'' of cities drawing Japanese interest, <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said, because its so-called `` trophy properties'' are available at cheaper rates than in the `` first-tier'' cities of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. There also is less competition in cities such as <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> to purchase trophy properties _ defined loosely by <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> as `` quality real estate, architecturally significant with a major tenant.'' The pending purchase of the IBM Tower by <ORGANIZATION> Sumitomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` is the big foot in our pond,'' <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said, and more such deals should follow fairly soon. Such deals have been aided by the recent strength of the Japanese yen over the dollar and by <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s expected strong growth in the next several years. The combination makes real estate investments particularly attractive. Among foreign investors, the Japanese have the most money and are the most aggressive, <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said. In addition, he said, the Japanese feel pressure from their peers to invest in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The Consulate General of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> says there were 236 Japanese-owned facilities in the state as of July 1, employing 12,100 people and representing an investment of $ 810 million. A report last year by the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> said there were six Taiwanese-owned facilities and four owned by <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION>. Two investors were from <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and one from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Of those Asian-owned businesses, 38 are headquarters for <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> subsidiaries, including <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes telecommunications equipment; <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, athletic shoe manufacturer; <ORGANIZATION> Mizuno </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Golf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest sporting goods company; and <ORGANIZATION> TDK </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> -RRB- </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, manufacturer of video cassette tapes There are numerous regional headquarters, and manufacturing plants for some of the best-known Japanese products, including <ORGANIZATION> Maxell </ORGANIZATION> tapes, <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> records, <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> televisions and <PERSON> Kubota </PERSON> tractors. There are also nine Japanese banks, and <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> said a 10th is expected to open soon. In all, there were 1,057 foreign-owned facilities in the state last year, the Industry and Trade report said. The department said Japanese capital investment ranked second in the state behind <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Just last week, the <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> opened its <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> golf car factory at <LOCATION> Newnan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, its first North American manufacturing facility. Some of that investment may have been driven by fears the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would enact severely protectionist trade legislation. Despite passage of a watered-down trade bill, <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said he does n't expect the flood of foreign investment to slow anytime soon.
