<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Oct. 31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Making it in Atlanta, Korean Style</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Buying Atlanta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Joon </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Song </PERSON> moved to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> 26 years ago, there were three Korean families in town. `` Then my brother came, and my sister, my father,'' <PERSON> Song </PERSON> said. Other families followed, and now, Song estimates, there are between 15,000 and 20,000 Koreans living in the metropolitan area of 2.5 million people. There are also an estimated 30,000 to 40,000 Chinese and about 5,000 Japanese, according to <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Judd </PERSON>, an independent business consultant who has spent much of the past two decades promoting <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> business connections in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. A recent study disclosed that many of those Asian-Americans own their own businesses _ so many that <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> ranked third in the country behind <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> in the number of Asian-owned businesses per 1,000 Asian residents. The study said there are 80.5 Asian-owned businesses per 1,000 Asian-Americans in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> was first with 90.3, followed by <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> at 84.9. Places with large Asian populations such as <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> were far down the list. The finding surprised Song, a past president of the <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an umbrella organization of 72 Korean support groups in the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> metropolitan area. `` Just like the Irish went to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> -LRB- and -RRB- the Polish went to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, Koreans and Chinese came to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Judd </PERSON>, a founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan-America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Song estimates that about 70 percent of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s Asians are direct immigrants with the rest coming from other major <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities They are drawn, he said, by the same factors that have made <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and the rest of the Sunbelt some of the fastest growing areas in the country. `` Weather's good. Transportation's good. Lots of things -LRB- are -RRB- good,'' said Song, who works for <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in Oriental business development. The new arrivals also find a strong sense of community, 42 Korean churches, a Korean-American school and a Korean chamber of commerce. `` Most of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> business is family business, that's why the business is growing very fast,'' Song said. The exact <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> population of the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> is hard to judge, with the latest figures coming from the 1980 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Census and most experts agreeing the numbers have changed substantially since then.
</TEXT>
