<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market was little changed today as prices withstood profit-taking and takeover speculation. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off .18 at 2,170.16 at midafternoon. Losers narrowly outpaced gainers by about 8 to 7 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed issues, with 640 up, 730 down and 521 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 110.76 million shares as of 2 p.m. on Wall Street. Traders were encouraged that the market did not lose ground as it consolidated in the face of a two-month-old rally. `` The profit-taking has been well contained,'' one trader said. The market, however, has divided into two unequal segments _ one that involves takeover and buyout issues and another that involves the remaining equities untouched by real bids or speculation. Billion-dollar bids have been made recently for such big-name companies as <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point-Pepperell </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. Large bids tend to put the spotlight on the industries of target companies, fueling further speculation about a target company's peers as potential takeover candidates. `` Takeover speculation has reached a new extreme,'' said <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> A.G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. `` The crescendo keeps getting louder and louder.'' The rest of the market, however, is not awash with excitement. Analysts said the broad market appears tired and unable to mount a sustainable advance. A government report showing a 4.1 percent drop in durable goods orders in September was within market expectations. The report, which hinted that inflation is being held in check, coupled with stability in the bond and currency markets helped support stock prices, said <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Geronimous </PERSON>, a senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Among <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> takeover issues, <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON> was up -RCB- at 84 -RCB-; <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> fell 3 to 99, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> was off -LRB- at 59 -LCB-, and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point-Pepperell </LOCATION> was off | at 49 -RRB-. Elsewhere, <ORGANIZATION> Rorer </ORGANIZATION> rose 2 ~ to 44 ~ amid speculation that F. Hoffman-LaRoche might launch a $ 60-a-share takeover <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> declined comment. Church's Fried Chicken was up -RCB- at 8. The company received an $ 8-a-share bid from Popeyes Fried Chicken. <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> plunged 8 -RCB- to 60 -LRB- following the release of lower-than-expected earnings for the third quarter. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all its listed common stocks slipped .14 to 158.71. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index was off .93 at 304.04.
