<HEAD>Goodyear Reports Earnings Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday said its third-quarter profits fell 65 percent from a year ago partly because of difficult business conditions in its domestic tire operations. For the quarter ended Sept. 30, <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 63.5 million, or $ 1.11 a share. A year earlier, the company reported net income of $ 178.7 million, or $ 3.13 a share. In the year-ago period, <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> benefited from a $ 50 million gain on the sale of properties in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. Sales, however, rose 8 percent to $ 2.7 billion, from $ 2.5 billion a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> attributed the recent decline in profits partly to higher natural rubber costs in its domestic tire operations. Plant efficiencies also were reduced due to an unusually hot summer, when the company was forced to cut back on electricity at some plants. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> began a major cost-cutting effort and shed most of its non-rubber operations beginning in late 1986 to raise cash and fend off a hostile takeover attempt by financier Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>. Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> said the company experienced a lag in recovering costs through price increases. Tire unit sales in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> replacement market were down in the three months, although the decline was partially offset by better unit sales of lower priced tires to original equipment manufacturers. The company indicated its businesses in 27 foreign countries showed improved earnings, but they were partially offset by greater foreign currency lossses. Through the nine months, <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> earned fell 51 percent to $ 293.7 million, or $ 5.13 a share, on sales of $ 8.1 billion. In the year-ago period, earnings were $ 603.9 million, or $ 9.78 a share, on sales of $ 7.4 billion.
