<HEAD>Control Data Reports First Loss After Four Profitable Quarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> on Tuesday blamed market `` softness'' in key business sectors for causing the computer company to post a net loss in the third quarter, its first loss after four profitable quarters. Another computer company, <ORGANIZATION> Storage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said its profit fell 76 percent in the latest quarter. Data-storage devices for mainframe computers are Storage Technology's principal business and make up about one-third of the revenue of <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> said it had a net loss of $ 2.4 million on revenues of $ 841.4 million for the quarter ending Sept. 30. In the third quarter of 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> had net earnings of $ 6.8 million, or 16 cents per share, on revenues of $ 831.4 million. For the first nine months of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> reported net earnings of $ 14.5 million, or 34 cents a share, on revenues of $ 2.7 billion, compared with earnings of $ 8.5 million, or 19 cents a share, on revenues of $ 2.4 billion over the same period last year. `` We are disappointed that <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION>'s 1988 results will come in below mid-year expectations,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chief executive officer. `` Nevertheless, the company's recovery remains on track, and we continue to anticipate that <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION>'s operating performance in 1988 will be stronger than it was in 1987. Control Data's computer systems and services division has received expected revenues later than anticipated, a trend that is expected to continue into the fourth quarter, according to company spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Foltz </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> said its results were helped by applying tax benefits in the quarter worth $ 4.8 million. Third-quarter results also benefited from the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION>'s interest in <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Imprimis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the company's disk drive subsidiary, exceeded its third quarter 1987 performance and 1988 plan, even though results for the period just ended were below those reported in the first and second quarters of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> said Storage Technology, of <LOCATION> Lousville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, which emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy court protection last year, said its profit fell to $ 752,000, or less than 1 cent a share, from $ 3.2 million, or 1 cent a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $ 128.3 million from $ 107 million. For the first nine months of its fiscal year, <ORGANIZATION> Storage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> said its profit fell to $ 15.7 million, or 7 cents a share, from $ 20.4 million, or 9 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $ 372.9 million from $ 301 million.
