<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished mixed against major foreign currencies Tuesday, weighed down by a government report of a slowdown in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factory orders. The dollar edged down against the British pound and the Japanese yen, but rose against the currencies of most other major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading partners. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said orders for `` big-ticket'' durable goods plunged an unexpected 4.1 percent in September. Currency traders took the decline as a sign that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy could be slowing down, something that would tend to decrease demand for dollars by foreign investors. The factory orders report fit in with other signs of a slowdown last month, including the second consecutive decline in retail sales and a drop in manufacturing employment. The dollar's decline against the British pound was partly the result of a speech by <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Chancellor of the Exchequer, that supported sterling, according to <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Conte </PERSON>, a vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar edged up 0.27 Japanese yen to a closing 126.87 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it rose to 127.75 yen. At the end of the day in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar fell to 126.80 yen from 127.02. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost $ 1.7535 to buy one pound, up from $ 1.7520 late Monday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound rose to $ 1.7515 from $ 1.7501 Monday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday's rates, included: 1.7903 West German marks, up from 1.7898; 1.5183 Swiss francs, up from 1.5175; 1.2012 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1986; 6.1230 French francs, 6.1100; and 1,333.75 Italian lire, up from 1,332.88 Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday's rates, included: 1.7860 West German marks, unchanged; 1.5175 Swiss francs, up from 1.5145; 6.1100 French francs, up from 6.1025; 2.0170 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0143; 1,332.00 Italian lire, up from 1,330.85; and 1.1990 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1973 Gold recovered some of its losses from Monday, when it had fallen after eight key members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> failed to agree on production restrictions. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose 32 cents to close at a bid $ 408.52 a troy ounce. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 407.25 an ounce from $ 405.15 Monday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, it rose to $ 407 an ounce from $ 405.50. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold bullion was bid at $ 406.60 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $ 405.50 late Monday. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold for near-month delivery rose to $ 406.40 an ounce from $ 405.80 Monday. Silver bullion rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid of $ 6.25 a troy ounce from $ 6.23 late Monday. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for near-month delivery rose to $ 6.221 an ounce from $ 6.197.
