> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was interested in buying <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION>. Both companies have disparaged the rumors. `` Whoever would be buying <ORGANIZATION> DEC </ORGANIZATION> would need an awfully big checkbook,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosak </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Eberstadt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION>'s stock hit a peak of $ 199.50 in 1987, but has slumped badly since then. The company has no dividend to support the stock, so buybacks are one of the few ways to reward shareholders. `` We believe buying our stock is an attractive investment and a sound way to build a shareholder value,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Osterhoff </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for finance, said in a news release. Digital purchased 3 million shares of its stock for $ 363 million in January and 5 million shares for $ 782 million in a program completed in May 1987. Those shares were used for employee stock plans.
