<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   10-25 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Slows As Takeover Mania Subsides</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market finished narrowly mixed Tuesday as a feeding frenzy in takeover issues subsided. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, off 13 points Monday, gained 3.02 to close at 2,173.36. The key index had seesawed within a 2-point range for much of the session. Declining issues narrowly outpaced advancers in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 701 issues up, 727 down and 525 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> came to 155.19 million shares, down from 170.59 million. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 183.30 million shares. The market appeared steady throughout most of the session as little fresh takeover news emerged. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Puccio </PERSON>, a senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Dillon </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Read </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, noted that the market `` has kind of dried up'' following a recent string of multibillion-dollar takeover announcements involving companies with high-profile brand names. But while stocks that are the target of deals and takeover speculation have basked in the spotlight, the broader market has missed much of the enthusiasm. `` The broader market seems to have settled back into its malaise,'' said <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` People seem to have retreated to the sidelines until another news event comes along,'' he said. On a more subtle level, some analysts are beginning to wonder whether some skepticism is s