CATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the offer is `` reasonable and fair in one sense.'' `` However, in this day and age of takeovers, the first offer is generally not the last from the original offeree,'' <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> said. `` Generally, the company under siege will try to come up with a higher alternative offer.'' The offer, which is to expire at midnight Nov. 22, is conditioned upon tender of enough shares to give <ORGANIZATION> Copeland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> two-thirds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s shares on a fully-diluted basis and upon obtaining sufficient financing <ORGANIZATION> Copeland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> said it already owns nearly 1.2 million shares, or 3.2 percent, of Church's shares. `` We intend to pursue it on an amicable basis,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>'s president. <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>, Popeyes chairman and chief executive, said in a statement, `` The combination of Popeyes' proven industry expertise in generating high per store sales on the basis of a superior quality menu and Church's loyal customer base in its core markets will create a dynamic fast-food restaurant operation.'' Church's board of directors said it will make a recommendation to its stockholders by Nov. 7 whether they should accept the offer and why. `` Church's requests that its stockholders defer making a decision to accept or reject the offer until they have been advised of the company's position,'' the company said in a statement. Church's is the second-largest purveyor of fast-food chicken in the country behind No. 1 <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION> New Orleans-based Popeyes, founded in 1972, is the third largest, said <ORGANIZATION> Sawyer-Mil