<HEAD>Profits Up At Mobil, Texaco, Chevron, Phillips; Down At Shell,
Amerada</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Jere in graf 18 is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Four of the nation's oil companies reported huge gains in their third-quarter profits Tuesday as hefty demand in refining and marketing segments offset declining crude oil prices. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> each reported double-digit gains, while profits at <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Phillips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> more than doubled in the latest period. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Amerada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> each reported sharp declines in their net earnings due partly to declining crude oil prices. The larger oil companies said earnings were both hurt and helped by falling crude prices. Lower costs for the raw product contributed to higher profit margins in refining and marketing operations but eroded gains in exploration and production. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> said his company's refining and marketing segments turned in strong performances thanks to improved margins stemming from tight refinery capacity and product inventories. In addition, strong consumer demand boosted sales of gasoline and lubricants. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>'s chemical unit also reported a record quarter, <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> said. However, those improvements were partially offset by a 26 percent drop in crude prices and higher exploration costs, which lowered the companies' profits from exploration and production. Analysts attribute most of this year's drop in crude prices to the excess supply of oil on world markets arising from the failure of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> to restrain its production. For the latest quarter, New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> had an after-tax profit of $ 557 million, or $ 1.36 a share, up 69 percent from $ 330 million, or 80 cents a share, in the year-ago period. Revenue totaled $ 13.12 billion, down a fraction from $ 13.14 billion in the year-ago period. For the first nine months, profits at the nation's second-largest oil company rose 86 percent to $ 1.62 billion, or $ 3.95 a share, compared with $ 874 million, or $ 2.13 a share, in the same period last year. Revenue totaled $ 40.99 billion, up 10 percent from $ 37.12 billion in the year-earlier period. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's third-largest oil company based in <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, reported a 121 percent rise in its third-quarter profits, to $ 239 million, or 98 cents a share, from $ 108 million, or 44 cents a share, in the 1987 quarter. Sales totaled $ 8.69 billion, down 3 percent from $ 8.96 billion last year. For the first nine months, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s profits jumped 183 percent to $ 1.01 billion, or $ 4.14 a share, compared with $ 355 million, or $ 1.46 a share, for the same period in 1987. Revenue totaled $ 26.8 billion, up 3 percent from $ 26 billion in the 1987 period. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON> said the company is beginning to see benefits from its recent restructuring. San Francisco-based <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>, the fourth-largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil concern, said its profits rose 41 percent to $ 420 million, or $ 1.23 a share, in the third quarter, compared with $ 297 million, or 87 cents a share, in the 1987 period. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s revenue, meanwhile, dropped 6.4 percent in the latest quarter to $ 7.2 billion, from $ 7.7 billion last year. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings jumped 57 percent to $ 1.6 billion, or $ 4.66 a share, from $ 1.01 billion, or $ 2.97 a share. Its revenue rose to $ 22 billion, up 1.3 percent from $ 21.7 billion. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Bartlesville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, reported the strongest quarterly profit gains _ nearly sixfold _ to $ 215 million, or 89 cents a share, from $ 31 million, or 11 cents a share. The company's sales totaled $ 2.85 billion, up a fraction from $ 2.80 billion Since January, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>' net surged to $ 515 million, or $ 2.17 a share, from $ 2 million in the comparable 1987 period. It had revenue of $ 8.5 billion, up 7.6 percent from $ 7.9 billion. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>' spokesman <PERSON> Jere </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said a major streamlining, which included the layoff of more than 1,500 workers, contributed to the latest figures. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>, the sixth-largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil company, said sagging crude prices pulled its quarterly earnings down 16.2 percent. The company's net was $ 352 million on revenue of $ 5.4 billion, compared with $ 420 million in the 1987 quarter on sales of $ 5.6 billion. The company does not report per-share figures. But for the first nine months, Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>'s net improved 134 percent to $ 1.9 billion, on revenue of $ 15.9 billion, compared with a profit in the same period last year of $ 795 million, on revenue of $ 15.3 billion. Lower crude prices also contributed to a 47 percent drop in <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION>'s latest earnings, which declined 47 percent to $ 72 million, or 67 a share, from $ 137 million, or $ 1.27 a share Its revenue totaled $ 2.46 billion, down 2.3 percent from $ 2.52 billion. Sun, headquartered in <LOCATION> Radnor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, reported a $ 69 million loss for the first nine months, on revenue of $ 7.3 billion, compared with a profit of $ 265 million in 1987, or $ 2.44 a share, on revenue of $ 7.2 billion. New York-based <PERSON> Amerada </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> reported a 59 percent decline in its quarterly net to $ 15.8 million, or 20 cents a share, from $ 38.6 million, or 45 cents a share. The company's revenue fell 17.5 percent to $ 925 million from $ 1.1 billion. In the first nine months, <PERSON> Amerada </PERSON> reported an 81 percent decline in earnings to $ 57 million, or 71 cents a share, on revenue of $ 3.1 billion, from $ 309 million, or $ 3.66 a share, on revenue of $ 3.5 billion.
