<FIRST>u f AM-DebtorNation 1stLd-Writethru f0278 10-25 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Debtor Nation, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0278,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Disputes Depth of U.S. International Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs The study... to CORRECT figure to minus $263
billion sted million. Picks up 6th graf, In 1988...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s international debt is far smaller than the government's figures indicate, according to a new study whose authors say misleading figures have led to exaggerated fears of economic decline. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to have become a net debtor nation in 1985, actually remained in the black until last year, according to the study by the <ORGANIZATION> Rand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` The big point about this is ... that the public debate has been misinformed and ill-served by frequent reiteration of flawed numbers,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of Rand's international economic policy research, said Tuesday. The figure in question, called the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> international investment position, is a cumulative total of all American spending and investment overseas compared to foreign spending and investment in this country. The study by the government-funded think tank indicates that in 1985, when <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> figures showed the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was a net debtor to the tune of $ 112 billion, the country actually was a $ 178 billion net creditor. In 1986, when the government figure was a minus $ 263 billion, the Rand recalculation had the country a creditor nation by $ 50 billion. In 1988, government figures indicated the country was $ 368 billion in debt. Rand researchers have n't calculated their version of the 1988 number, but know it would be negative, <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said. The Rand study, conducted under <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>'s direction by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> graduate student <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooker </PERSON>, adjusts the government's measures in several ways: _ It converts `` direct investment,'' the department's measure of private holdings of foreign capital, including real estate, to current dollar Because much American investment overseas was made years ago, when the dollar was worth less than today, this increases the vaue of Americans' foreign holdings relative to foreigners' more recent investments in this country. _ It boosts the value of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gold reserves, another component of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> figure, by using a market price of $ 380 per ounce rather than the department's `` official'' price of $ 42.22 an ounce _ On the negative side, the researchers cut the value of loans owed to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks by developing nations Based on the theory that many of these shaky loans will never be repaid, the study fixed their value at what they would bring on the secondary market, where banks trade debts of various kinds. These adjustments reflect previously voiced criticism of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> figures. But the researchers believe they are the first to actually recalculate the department numbers based on the criticism, <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said. Even after the changes, the numbers show a steady slide in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position. That is n't necessarily bad, <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said, to the extent that it represents foreigners' confidence in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> economy as a safe, stable haven for their money. `` The point is, you do n't contribute to what we like to think of as an informed and educated debate by using figures that are $ 300 million off the mark,'' <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said. `` ... There's a perception problem in how you view the situation: Is it grave, or serious, or just a matter of concern. ... I think it's a matter of concern.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
