earnings, edit to conform. Picks up 4th graf, Capital Cities-ABC
said... ADDS 3 grafs with Washington Post details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday it had a 63 percent jump in its third-quarter income, while the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported its profit was down by 39.6 percent from a year-earlier period when it had large one-time gains. Capital Cities-ABC, which owns the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> television network and other broadcast and print properties, said it earned $ 62.6 million, or $ 3.55 a share, during the quarter ended Sept. 30. That was up from $ 38.4 million, or $ 2.23 a share, in the same period of 1987. The company reported revenue of nearly $ 1.01 billion, up from $ 946.21 billion in the third quarter a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that it had a profit of $ 38.1 million, or $ 2.96 per share, in the three months ended Sept. 30, compared with $ 63.1 million, or $ 4.77 per share, in the year-earlier period. Sales rose to $ 329.4 million from $ 312.9 million in third-quarter 1987. Capital Cities-ABC said its broadcasting operations had a 24 percent rise in income, while income from its publishing operations was flat. For the first nine months of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION> said it earned $ 246.9 million, or $ 14.43 a share, up from $ 162.1 million, or $ 9.56 a share, in the same period of 1987. The company reported nine-month revenue of $ 3.46 billion, up from $ 3.03 billion a year earlier. Capital-Cities-ABC also owns six radio networks, eight television stations and 21 radio stations. It provides programming for cable television, and its publishing businesses includes daily and weekly newspapers, specialty and business periodicals and books. The third quarter 1987 profit for <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> included one-time after-tax gains of $ 30.2 million, or $ 2.35 per share, from the sales of certain cellular telephone and <ORGANIZATION> SportsChannel </ORGANIZATION> cable television interests. Newspaper division revenue increased 8 percent in the third quarter over the comparable period last year, according to the company report. Post-Newsweek television stations' revenue was up 5 percent in the third quarter, and cable division revenue increased 17 percent. For the nine months, the company had a profit of $ 232.2 million, or $ 18.04 per share, compared with $ 122.3 million, or $ 9.51 per share, in the same period of 1987. Revenue during the nine months rose to $ 996.8 million from $ 950.4 million.
