<HEAD>China To Impose Export Tax on Silk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Wednesday will begin levying export tariffs of up to 100 percent on silk and its products to stop a `` silk cocoon war'' that has pushed up prices. The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the 100 percent tariff will be levied on silkworm cocoon, raw silk, waste silk, silk yarn and spun silk. Duties on silk, silk noil and fabrics made of waste silk will be 80 percent, it said. The new duties, announced by the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tariff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION>, will affect all silk exports regardless of when contracts were signed. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> produces about 50,000 tons of cocoon silk annually, of which 70 percent is for export. Ninety percent of raw silk and 40 percent of gray silk goods on international markets come from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, according to the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION>. The Chinese government last month stated the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Silk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Export </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> will undertake the unified handling of silkworm cocoons, including exports, to halt the price war among trading companies competing for scarce cocoons. It banned all other departments and individuals from purchasing or handling silkworm cocoons and said Sino-foreign joint ventures must apply for export permits in accordance with state-assigned export quotas. Despite increasing demand for <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> silk, cocoon production has declined recently due to bad weather and low state-set prices. Factories in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and other cities have been forced to stop production because of shortages of cocoons and filature silk. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Daily reported last week that Chinese silk traders were turning down new customers at the <ORGANIZATION> Canton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> and there would be a sharp drop in export contracts compared with previous fairs. It said <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> silk prices have risen by about 20 percent since last spring.
